{"title_page": "Eschiva of Ibelin, Lady of Beirut", "text_new": "{{Infobox noble|type\n| name              = Eschiva\n| title             = \n| image             = Armoiries Ibelin.svg\n| image_size = 150px\n| caption           = Coat-of-arms of Ibelin.\n| succession        = Lady of Beirut\n| reign             = 1282 - 1312\n| predecessor       = [[Isabella of Beirut]]\n| successor         = [[Rupen of Montfort]]\n| spouse            = [[Humphrey of Montfort]]<br>[[Guy, Constable of Cyprus]]\n| issue             = [[Rupen of Montfort]]<br>[[Hugh IV of Cyprus]]<br>Isabelle\n| noble family      = [[House of Ibelin]]-Beirut\n| father            = [[John II of Beirut]]\n| mother            = [[Alice de la Roche]] of Athens\n| birth_date        = 1253\n| birth_place       =\n| death_date        = 1312\n}}\n\n'''Eschive d'Ibelin''' (1253\u20131312) was ''[[suo jure]]'' [[Lady of Beirut]] in 1282-1312. She was the daughter of [[John II of Beirut]] (died 1264), [[lord of Beirut]], and of [[Alice de la Roche]], and a member of the influential [[Ibelin family]].\n\n==Life==\n\nShe first married, in 1274, [[Humphrey of Montfort (died 1284)|Humphrey de Montfort]], [[lord of Tyre]] (died 1284).{{sfn|Edbury|2001|p=24}}\n\n===Lady of Beirut===\nShe became lady of Beirut on the death of her sister [[Isabella of Beirut|Isabelle of Beirut]] in 1282.\n\nAfter Humphrey's death, she remarried in 1291 [[Guy constable of Cyprus|Guy of Lusignan]], constable of Cyprus (died 1302).{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=37}}\n\nIn 1291, Emir \u2018Alam al-Din Sanjar al-Shuja\u2018i al-Mansuri, a [[Muslim]] general under [[al-Ashraf Khalil]], marched on Beirut, which had only a small garrison. Eschive thought she was secure because she had signed a truce with [[Qalawun]], father of Khalil. Al-Shuja\u2018i summoned the commanders of the garrison and arrested them. Seeing the commanders arrested, the population fled by sea. Beirut was taken by the Muslims on July 31. Al-Shuja\u2018i ordered the razing of its walls and castles and turned its cathedral into a mosque.\n\n=== Claimant to the Duchy of Athens ===\n\nIn 1308, Eschive's cousin [[Guy II de la Roche]], [[Duke of Athens]], died without issue, leaving a succession crisis in the duchy. Eschive travelled to the [[Morea]] in the same year to claim her rights to the duchy of Athens. She was one of the two claimants, as the daughter of Guy's aunt Alice; her rival, [[Walter V of Brienne]], was the son of Guy's aunt [[Isabella de la Roche|Isabella]], a younger sister of Alice. Upon her return journey from Morea, Eschive was shipwrecked. Since Athens was a [[fief]] of the [[Principality of Achaea]], the decision was in the hands of [[Philip I of Taranto]], [[Prince of Achaea]], and his suzerain and elder brother [[Robert of Naples]]. The two referred the question to the High Court of Achaea in 1309, which met at [[Glarentza]] and declared Walter the heir on the pragmatic grounds that he was male and an active soldier, better suited to defend the Duchy. The disappointed Eschive thereupon appealed to the [[Virgin Mary]] before the altar of St Francis at Glarentza, asking that Walter and the judges die without heirs of the body if they had wrongly judged against her.{{sfn|Miller|1908|p=220-221}} Eschive in fact outlived Walter, who was killed at the [[Battle of Halmyros]] in 1311, but died the following year in [[Nicosia]] and was buried there.\n\n== Issue ==\nWith [[Humphrey of Montfort (died 1284)|Humphrey de Montfort]], [[lord of Tyre]] (died 1284),{{sfn|Edbury|2001|p=24}} they had:\n* Three sons and one daughter, all who died young\n* Amaury de Montfort (died 1304){{sfn|Edbury|2001|p=24}}\n* [[Rupen de Montfort]] (died 1313){{sfn|Edbury|2001|p=24}}\n\nWith [[Guy constable of Cyprus|Guy of Lusignan]], constable of Cyprus (died 1302),{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=37}} they had:\n* [[Hugh IV of Cyprus|Hugh IV]] (1295\u20131359) king of Cyprus, married firstly Maria of Ibelin, then Alice of Ibelin{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=37}}\n* Isabelle de Lusignan (born 1298), who in 1322 married Eudes de Dampierre (died 1330){{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=37}}\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n| 1= '''Eschive d'Ibelin'''\n| 2= [[John II of Beirut|John II d'Ibelin, lord of Beirut]]\n| 3= [[Alice de la Roche|Alice de la Roche of Athens]]\n| 4= [[Balian of Beirut|Balian d'Ibelin, lord of Beirut]]\n| 5= Eschiva de Montfaucon\n| 6= [[Guy I de la Roche|Guy I de la Roche, duke of Athens]]\n| 7= ... de Bruyeres\n| 8= [[John of Ibelin, the Old Lord of Beirut|John I d'Ibelin, lord of Beirut]]\n| 9= Melisende, lady of Arsuf\n|10= [[Walter of Montb\u00e9liard]]\n|11= Burgundia de Lusignan of Cyprus\n|12= [[Othon de la Roche|Othon de la Roche, duke of Athens]]\n|13= Isabel (Elisabeth)\n|14= \n|15= \n|16= [[Balian of Ibelin|Balian d'Ibelin]]\n|17= [[Maria Komnene, Queen of Jerusalem|Maria Komnene]]\n|18= Guy of Arsuf\n|19=   \n|20= [[Amadeus II of Montfaucon|Amadeus II, count of Montfaucon]]\n|21= Beatrice Grandson-Joinville\n|22= [[Aimery of Cyprus|Aimery de Lusignan, king of Cyprus]]\n|23= [[Eschive d'Ibelin (1160\u20131196)|Eschive d'Ibelin]]\n|24= Pons de La Roche\n|25= \n|26= \n|27= \n|28= \n|29= \n|30= \n|31= \n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book |title=The Kingdom of Cyprus and the Crusades, 1191-1374 |first=Peter W. |last=Edbury |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1994 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |chapter=The De Montforts in the Latin East |first=Peter W. |last=Edbury |title=Thirteenth Century England VIII: Proceedings of the Durham Conference 1999 |editor-first1=Michael |editor-last1=Prestwich |editor-first2=R. H. |editor-last2=Britnell |editor-first3=Robin |editor-last3=Frame |publisher=The Boydell Press |year=2001 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book | last=Miller | first=William | title=The Latins in the Levant: A History of Frankish Greece (1204&ndash;1566) | publisher=J. Murray | pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_5UztIt_jIoUC/page/n242 220]&ndash;221 | location=London | year=1908 | url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_5UztIt_jIoUC | accessdate=2008-07-18 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Isabella of Ibelin (1252-1282)|Isabella of Ibelin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord_of_Beirut#Lordship_of_Beirut|Lady of Beirut]]|years=1282\u20131291\n|regent1=[[Humphrey of Montfort (died 1284)|Humphrey of Montfort]]|years1=1282\u20131284\n|regent2=[[Guy of Cyprus (died 1302)|Guy of Cyprus]]|years2=1291}}\n{{s-vac|reason=Conquest by [[Al-Ashraf Khalil]]|next=[[Rupen de Montfort]]|as=claimant}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eschive D'ibelin (1253-1312)}}\n[[Category:1253 births]]\n[[Category:1312 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of the Kingdom of Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Women of the Crusader states]]\n[[Category:House of Ibelin]]\n[[Category:History of Beirut]]\n[[Category:Women of the Duchy of Athens]]\n[[Category:13th-century women rulers]]\n[[Category:14th-century women rulers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox noble|type\n| name              = Eschiva\n| title             = \n| image             = Armoiries Ibelin.svg\n| image_size = 150px\n| caption           = Coat-of-arms of Ibelin.\n| succession        = Lady of Beirut\n| reign             = 1282 - 1312\n| predecessor       = [[Isabella of Beirut]]\n| successor         = [[Rupen of Montfort]]\n| spouse            = [[Humphrey of Montfort]]<br>[[Guy, Constable of Cyprus]]\n| issue             = [[Rupen of Montfort]]<br>[[Hugh IV of Cyprus]]<br>Isabelle\n| noble family      = [[House of Ibelin]]-Beirut\n| father            = [[John II of Beirut]]\n| mother            = [[Alice de la Roche]] of Athens\n| birth_date        = 1253\n| birth_place       =\n| death_date        = 1312\n}}\n\n'''Eschive d'Ibelin''' (1253\u20131312) was ''[[suo jure]]'' [[Lady of Beirut]] in 1282-1312. She was the daughter of [[John II of Beirut]] (died 1264), [[lord of Beirut]], and of [[Alice de la Roche]], and a member of the influential [[Ibelin family]].\n\n==Life==\n\nShe first married, in 1274, [[Humphrey of Montfort (died 1284)|Humphrey de Montfort]], [[lord of Tyre]] (died 1284).{{sfn|Edbury|2001|p=24}}\n\n===Lady of Beirut===\nShe became lady of Beirut on the death of her sister [[Isabelle d'Ibelin (1252-1282)|Isabelle d'Ibelin]] in 1282.\n\nAfter Humphrey's death, she remarried in 1291 [[Guy constable of Cyprus|Guy of Lusignan]], constable of Cyprus (died 1302).{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=37}}\n\nIn 1291, Emir \u2018Alam al-Din Sanjar al-Shuja\u2018i al-Mansuri, a [[Muslim]] general under [[Al-Ashraf Khalil]], marched on Beirut, which had only a small garrison. Eschive thought she was secure because she had signed a truce with [[Qalawun]], father of Khalil. Al-Shuja\u2018i summoned the commanders of the garrison and arrested them. Seeing the commanders arrested, the population fled by sea. Beirut was taken by the Muslims on July 31. Al-Shuja\u2018i ordered the razing of its walls and castles and turned its cathedral into a mosque.\n\n=== Claimant to the Duchy of Athens ===\n\nIn 1308, Eschive's cousin [[Guy II de la Roche]], [[Duke of Athens]], died without issue, leaving a succession crisis in the duchy. Eschive travelled to the [[Morea]] in the same year to claim her rights to the duchy of Athens. She was one of the two claimants, as the daughter of Guy's aunt Alice; her rival, [[Walter V of Brienne]], was the son of Guy's aunt [[Isabella de la Roche|Isabella]], a younger sister of Alice. Upon her return journey from Morea, Eschive was shipwrecked. Since Athens was a [[fief]] of the [[Principality of Achaea]], the decision was in the hands of [[Philip I of Taranto]], [[Prince of Achaea]], and his suzerain and elder brother [[Robert of Naples]]. The two referred the question to the High Court of Achaea in 1309, which met at [[Glarentza]] and declared Walter the heir on the pragmatic grounds that he was male and an active soldier, better suited to defend the Duchy. The disappointed Eschive thereupon appealed to the [[Virgin Mary]] before the altar of St Francis at Glarentza, asking that Walter and the judges die without heirs of the body if they had wrongly judged against her.{{sfn|Miller|1908|p=220-221}} Eschive in fact outlived Walter, who was killed at the [[Battle of Halmyros]] in 1311, but died the following year in [[Nicosia]] and was buried there.\n\n== Issue ==\nWith [[Humphrey of Montfort (died 1284)|Humphrey de Montfort]], [[lord of Tyre]] (died 1284),{{sfn|Edbury|2001|p=24}} they had:\n* Three sons and one daughter, all who died young\n* Amaury de Montfort (died 1304){{sfn|Edbury|2001|p=24}}\n* [[Rupen de Montfort]] (died 1313){{sfn|Edbury|2001|p=24}}\n\nWith [[Guy constable of Cyprus|Guy of Lusignan]], constable of Cyprus (died 1302),{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=37}} they had:\n* [[Hugh IV of Cyprus|Hugh IV]] (1295\u20131359) king of Cyprus, married firstly Maria of Ibelin, then Alice of Ibelin{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=37}}\n* Isabelle de Lusignan (born 1298), who in 1322 married Eudes de Dampierre (died 1330){{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=37}}\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n| 1= '''Eschive d'Ibelin'''\n| 2= [[John II of Beirut|John II d'Ibelin, lord of Beirut]]\n| 3= [[Alice de la Roche|Alice de la Roche of Athens]]\n| 4= [[Balian of Beirut|Balian d'Ibelin, lord of Beirut]]\n| 5= Eschiva de Montfaucon\n| 6= [[Guy I de la Roche|Guy I de la Roche, duke of Athens]]\n| 7= ... de Bruyeres\n| 8= [[John of Ibelin, the Old Lord of Beirut|John I d'Ibelin, lord of Beirut]]\n| 9= Melisende, lady of Arsuf\n|10= [[Walter of Montb\u00e9liard]]\n|11= Burgundia de Lusignan of Cyprus\n|12= [[Othon de la Roche|Othon de la Roche, duke of Athens]]\n|13= Isabel (Elisabeth)\n|14=