    = 51 kg <!--Mass of gasses transferred (e.g. oxygen)-->\n| cargo_mass_water   = 420 kg <!--Mass of water transferred-->\n| programme          = Progress ISS Resupply\n| previous_mission   = [[Progress MS-11]]\n| next_mission       = [[Progress MS-13]]\n\n<!--mission insignia or patch-->| insignia = <!--omit the \"file\" prefix-->\n| insignia_caption = <!--image caption-->\n| insignia_alt = <!--image alt text-->\n| insignia_size = <!--include px/em; defaults to 180px-->\n}}\n\n'''Progress MS-12''' ({{Lang-ru|\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0441 \u041cC-12|italic=yes}}), identified by [[NASA]] as '''Progress 73''' or '''73P''', was a [[Progress (spacecraft)|Progress]] spacecraft used by [[Roscosmos State Corporation|Roscosmos]] to resupply the [[International Space Station]] (ISS).<ref name=russianspaceweb>http://russianspaceweb.com/progress-ms-12.html</ref>\n\n==Launch==\nThe launch was planned for 1 July 2018, rescheduled for 5 June 2019 and rescheduled to 31 July 2019.<ref>{{cite report|author=NASA Office of Inspector General|date=June 28, 2016|title=NASA's Response to SpaceX's June 2015 Launch Failure: Impacts on Commercial Resupply of the International Space Station|url=https://oig.nasa.gov/audits/reports/FY16/IG-16-025.pdf|publisher=NASA Office of Inspector General |format=PDF|issue=Report No. IG-16-025|page=13|access-date=2016-07-18}}</ref>\n\nProgress MS-12 was launched in 31 July 2019 12:10:46 UTC from [[Baikonur Cosmodrome]] in [[Kazakhstan]], using a [[Soyuz-2.1a]] rocket.<ref>http://russianspaceweb.com/progress-ms-12.html</ref>\n\n==Docking==\nProgress MS-12 docked with the [[Pirs (ISS module)|Pirs]] docking module. The docking took place 3 hours 18 minutes 31 seconds into the mission (a new record time).\n\n==Cargo==\nThe Progress MS-12 spacecraft delivered {{convert|1164|kg}} of dry cargo (in the cargo compartment), {{convert|420|kg}} of water (in the Rodnik-system tanks), {{convert|51|kg}} of oxygen (in pressurized bottles), {{convert|850|kg}} of propellant in the refueling section and {{convert|880|kg}} of propellant in the integrated propulsion system to the International Space Station. The dry cargo consisted of: {{convert|394|kg}} of hardware for onboard systems, {{convert|27|kg}} of medical supplies, {{convert|1|kg}} of personal protective gear, {{convert|190|kg}} of hygiene items, {{convert|7|kg}} of repairs and servicing equipment, {{convert|20|kg}} of means of crew support, {{convert|282|kg}} of food, {{convert|13|kg}} of payloads, {{convert|38|kg}} of structural components and other hardware and {{convert|192|kg}} of NASA cargo.<ref>http://russianspaceweb.com/progress-ms-12.html</ref>\n\n==End of mission==\nThe Progress craft undocked from ISS 29 November 2019 10:25 UTC, initiated braking maneuver 13:39 UTC, re-entered Earth's atmosphere 14:11 UTC (end of mission), with any remaining debris impacting a remote part of Pacific Ocean 14:19 UTC.<ref name=russianspaceweb/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n{{Progress spacecraft}}\n{{Unmanned ISS resupply flights}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2019}}\n\n[[Category:Progress (spacecraft) missions]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 2019]]\n[[Category:2019 in Russia]]\n[[Category:Supply vehicles for the International Space Station]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched by Soyuz-2 rockets]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft which reentered in 2019]]\n", "name_user": "CRS-20", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Progress_MS-12"}
{"title_page": "Ruth's Chris Steak House", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Ruth's Chris Steak House\n| logo             = Ruths Chris Logo.svg\n| type             = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as        = \n| foundation       = Broad Street, [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]] (1965)\n| location_city    = \n| location_country =\n| location         = [[Winter Park, Florida]]\n| locations        = 100+ [[steakhouse]]s<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=190038&p=irol-homeprofile</ref>\n| founder          = [[Ruth Fertel]]\n| key_people       = Mike O'Donnell ([[Chairman]] & [[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]]), Kevin Toomy ([[Chief Operating Officer]])\n| area_served      = United States <br> Canada <br> Aruba <br> Panama <br> Puerto Rico <br> Mexico <br> Singapore <br> China <br> Indonesia <br> Japan <br> Taiwan <br> Hong Kong\n| industry         = [[Restaurant]]s\n| products         = Food service\n| services         =\n| revenue          = [[United States dollar|US$]]468 million {{small|(FY 2019)}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Darby |first1=Luke |title=Ruth's Chris Made $468 Million in Revenue but Gobbled Up $20 Million in Small Business Relief |url=https://www.gq.com/story/ruths-chris-small-business-steakhouse |work=GQ |date=April 20, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| num_employees    = 5000+ (''2020'')<ref name=wsj/><ref name=\"hoovers.com\">{{cite web|url=http://hoovers.com/company/Ruths_Hospitality_Group_Inc/cthsif-1.html |title=Ruth's Hospitality Group, Inc. &#124; Company profile from Hoover's &#124; 407-333-7440 |publisher=Hoovers.com |date=October 21, 2010 |accessdate=January 25, 2012}}</ref>\n| parent           = [[Ruth's Hospitality Group]]\n| divisions        =\n| subsid           =\n| caption          =\n| homepage         = {{URL|www.ruthschris.com}}\n| dissolved        =\n| footnotes        =\n| intl             =\n}}\n\n'''Ruth's Chris Steak House''' is a chain of over 100 [[steakhouse]]s<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=190038&p=irol-homeprofile</ref> across the [[United States]], Canada and Mexico. On May 22, 2008, the company underwent rebranding and became part of [[Ruth's Hospitality Group]] after its acquisition of [[Mitchell's Fish Market]].<ref>[http://columbus.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2008/03/24/daily28.html?ana=yfcpc Ruth's Chris vying to change name], First of Columbus, March 27, 2008</ref> The group's headquarters are in [[Winter Park, Florida]].<ref>\"[http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/MapItDrawServlet?geo_id=16000US1229320&_bucket_id=50&tree_id=420&context=saff&_lang=en&_sse=on Heathrow CDP, Florida] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606041900/http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/MapItDrawServlet?geo_id=16000US1229320&_bucket_id=50&tree_id=420&context=saff&_lang=en&_sse=on |date=2011-06-06 }}.\" [[U.S. Census Bureau]]. Retrieved on February 26, 2010.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.ruthschris.com/HomeOffice Home Office] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100225054209/http://www.ruthschris.com/HomeOffice |date=2010-02-25 }}.\" Ruth's Hospitality Group. Retrieved on February 26, 2010.</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== The original Chris Steak House (1927\u20131965) ===\nChris Steak House was founded on February 27, 1927 by [[New Orleans]] entrepreneur Chris Matulich.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1998/07/06/244825/index.htm|title=So Just What Does 'Ruth's Chris' Mean?|work=Fortune|accessdate=July 11, 2019|date=July 6, 1998|author=Anne Faircloth}}</ref> It was located at 1100 North Broad Street near the [[Fair Grounds Race Course]], seated 60 people, and had no parking lot. During Matulich's 38-year management, the business was sold six times, failing each time, and enabling him to buy the restaurant back cheaply from the purchasers.<ref>Fortune Magazine, October 2003</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth's Chris Steak House History|url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/ruth-s-chris-steak-house-history/|work=Funding Universe|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Ownership by Ruth Fertel, 1965\u20131999 ===\n\n==== Acquisition, 1965 ====\n\n[[Ruth Fertel]] was a divorced single mother who needed money to send her teenage sons to college. Ignoring the advice of her banker, lawyer, and friends, Ruth purchased the restaurant in 1965.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth Fertel: A Pioneer in the Restaurant Industryauthor= Katie Bloor & Linda J Shea|url=http://people.umass.edu/q4/0%200%20Profiles/20-1%20Ruth%20Fertel%20paper.doc|work=HTM 591S \u2013 Foundations in Hospitality and Tourism Management|publisher=University of Massachusetts Amherst|accessdate=February 4, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402103935/http://people.umass.edu/q4/0%200%20Profiles/20-1%20Ruth%20Fertel%20paper.doc|archivedate=April 2, 2015}}</ref> She used her brother's restaurant, Sig's Antique Restaurant in Port Sulphur, Louisiana, along with family recipes to lay the foundation for her restaurant.<ref>{{cite web|title=The BP Oil Spill and the Bounty of Plaquemines Parish|author= Randy Fertel|url=http://www.gastronomica.org/bp-oil-spill-bounty-plaquemines-parish/|work=Gastronomica The Journal of Critical Food Studies|accessdate=January 2, 2015}}</ref> She initially planned to raise just $18,000 to cover the purchase price, until it was pointed out to her that she would need an additional $4,000 to cover the cost of renovations and food.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steamroller \u2013 Ruth Fertel|url=http://capitalistchicks.com/?q=node/527|work=Capitalist Chicks|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref> On her first day, May 24, 1965, she sold 35 steaks at $5 each.<ref name=\"Her Life Is The Stuff Of Legend\">{{cite web|title=Her Life Is The Stuff Of Legend|url=http://www.fertel.com/images/about_ruth.pdf|accessdate=February 4, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024163101/http://www.fertel.com/images/about_ruth.pdf|archivedate=October 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nFertel personally took a hand in every part of the business. She had to teach herself how to butcher steak, and despite being just five-foot-two and 110-pounds, would saw up 30-pound short loins by hand until she could afford an electric band saw. She staffed her restaurant with single mothers, saying that they were hard workers and reliable. For many years, Chris Steak House was the only upscale restaurant in New Orleans with an all-female wait staff.<ref name=\"Her Life Is The Stuff Of Legend\"/>\n\nFrom the beginning, her restaurant attracted local politicians as well as athletes, businessmen and reporters. Political reporter Rosemary James noted that she \"would not have missed a Friday before a major election at Ruth's Chris Steak House. That was the place to be if you wanted to get some scoops.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Randy Fertel, philanthropist and son of steakhouse founder Ruth and 'Gorilla Man' Rodney puts family's legacy into print|url=http://www.nola.com/dining/index.ssf/2011/10/randy_fertel_philanthropist_an.html|work=The Times-Picayune|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref> Local celebrities like [[Fats Domino]] were regulars.<ref name=\"bluetoad.com\">{{cite web|title=An Author Finds His Therapy Inside A Family Memoir|url=http://www.bluetoad.com/publication/?i=95286&p=38|work=De Soto: Exploring the South|date= January 2012|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Name change to ''Ruth's Chris Steak House'', 1976 ====\n\nIn early 1976, shortly after Fertel signed a new ten-year lease on the restaurant, a fire destroyed the building. Fertel had recently acquired a second property nearby to rent out as a party space. Within seven days, she had relocated the restaurant to its new location a few blocks away at 711 North Broad Street and re-opened it, expanding to 160 seats in the process.<ref name=\"Her Life Is The Stuff Of Legend\"/> The sales agreement with Matulich prevented her from using the original name at any other address, so she named the new restaurant ''Ruth's Chris Steak House'' in order to keep some continuity with the previous location.<ref>McDowell, Bill, \"Ruth's Chris Steak House,\" ''Restaurants & Institutions'', August 1, 1994, 54.</ref> She admitted later to ''Fortune Magazine'' that \"I've always hated the name, but we've always managed to work around it.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth Fertel of Steakhouse Fame Is Dead at 75|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/18/business/ruth-fertel-of-steakhouse-fame-is-dead-at-75.html|work=NY Times|date= April 18, 2002|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Expansion and franchising, 1976\u20131999 ====\nThe first franchised restaurant was opened in 1977 by a loyal customer, [[T. J. Moran|Thomas J. \"T. J.\" Moran]] (c. 1931\u20132015), in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana|Baton Rouge]], who went on to open several more franchised Ruth's Chris locations, TJ Ribs, and Ruffino's restaurants<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theadvocate.com/news/12405583-123/philanthropist-restaurateur-tj-moran-dies|title=Philanthropist, founder of TJ Ribs, Ruffino\u2019s restaurants T.J. Moran dies at age 84, family friend says: Restaurateur funded medical outreach|publisher=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|Baton Rouge Advocate]]|author=Bill Lodge|accessdate=May 19, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150520155406/http://theadvocate.com/news/12405583-123/philanthropist-restaurateur-tj-moran-dies|archivedate=May 20, 2015}}</ref> through his company T.J. Moran Associates. Fertel noted, \"All our franchisees were people who had eaten at one time or another in one of our restaurants. We never looked for franchisees. They came to us.\"<ref name=\"Her Life Is The Stuff Of Legend\"/> The chain expanded rapidly over the next two decades, with 66 locations in the U.S. and overseas by mid-1998,<ref>{{cite web|title=So Just What Does 'Ruth's Chris' Mean?|url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1998/07/06/244825/|work=CNN Money|date=July 6, 1998|accessdate=February 19, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130409095426/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1998/07/06/244825/|archivedate=April 9, 2013}}</ref><ref>\"Never Give Up: Ruth's Chris Steak House,\" ''Entrepreneur Magazine'', September 1997, 81.</ref> and achieving over $200 million in annual revenues.<ref name=\"articles.chicagotribune.com\">{{cite web|title=Madison Dearborn Finds Ruth's Chris To Be Tasty Morsel|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-07-20/business/9907200346_1_madison-dearborn-partners-ruth-fertel-kellogg|work=Chicago Tribune|date= July 20, 1999|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> This success earned Fertel a number of accolades as an entrepreneur, and the [[epithet]] ''The First Lady of American Restaurants'' or ''The Empress of Steak''.<ref name=\"bluetoad.com\"/>\n\n=== Acquisition by Madison Dearborn 1999\u20132005 ===\nIn 1999, Fertel, then 72, developed [[lung cancer]]. She sold a 79.3 percent interest in the chain in August 1999 to investment company [[Madison Dearborn|Madison Dearborn Partners]] of [[Chicago]], remaining as a shareholder until her death in 2002.<ref name=\"articles.chicagotribune.com\"/>\n\nIn that period, the chain expanded to 86 restaurants, including 10 overseas locations. Revenues fell to $167.8 million in 2003, before rising again to $192.2 million in 2004.\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth's Chris IPO to raise $235M|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/tampabay/stories/2005/04/25/daily12.html|work=Tampa Bay Business Journal|date= April 25, 2005|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Public company, 2005 onwards ===\n\nOn August 9, 2005, under President & CEO Craig Miller, Ruth's Chris Steak House became a [[public company]] following a successful [[IPO]] valuing the company at $235 million and an increase of 15 percent in first-day trading.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth's Chris Steak IPO sizzles|url=http://articles.marketwatch.com/2005-08-09/news/30713731_1_stock-market-debut-friedman-billings-renaissance-capital|work=Wall Street Journal|date=August 9, 2005|accessdate=February 19, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130411073426/http://articles.marketwatch.com/2005-08-09/news/30713731_1_stock-market-debut-friedman-billings-renaissance-capital|archivedate=April 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Relocation to Florida, 2005 ====\n\nIn late August 2005 [[Hurricane Katrina]] devastated [[Greater New Orleans]] (see: [[Effect of Hurricane Katrina on New Orleans]]), and  the chain moved its corporate headquarters to [[Heathrow, Florida]]. Like most businesses in the city, two of the chain's locations in the New Orleans area were forced to close because of the storm.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dash |first=Craig |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/09/business/09ruth.html?ex=1283918400&en=eed85083a22295e3&ei=5090&partner=rssuserland&emc=rss|title=Ruth Built the Steakhouse. Katrina Intervened |publisher=New York Times|date=September 5, 2005 |accessdate=April 22, 2007}}</ref> The [[Metairie, Louisiana|Metairie]] location has since reopened.<ref>http://www.ruthschris.com/Restaurant-Locations/metairie</ref> Members of the Fertel family, particularly Ruth's son Randy, were bitterly opposed to the move. Amid much criticism by local officials and media, and on the heels of the announcement by [[Morton's]] that it would reopen its own New Orleans branch,<ref>{{cite news |last=Fitzmorris |first=Tim |url=http://www.neworleanscitybusiness.com/viewStory.cfm?recID=14865 |title=Morton\u2019s beefs up city\u2019s diminished steak offerings |publisher=New Orleans City Business |date=February 27, 2006 |accessdate=April 22, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928075605/http://www.neworleanscitybusiness.com/viewStory.cfm?recID=14865 |archivedate=September 28, 2007 }}</ref> the corporate offices announced that, due to extensive damage, the old flagship location on Broad Street would be permanently closed and donated to charity.<ref>[http://www.ruthschris.com/news/details.php?id=43 Press Release] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061231005420/http://www.ruthschris.com/news/details.php?id=43 |date=December 31, 2006 }}, Ruth's Chris Steakhouse, Inc., November 18, 2005.</ref> [[Tulane University]] was the recipient of the gift, remodeling and reopening the site in 2012 as the Ruth U. Fertel/Tulane Community Health Center.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rickard|first=Mary|url=http://blog.nola.com/new_orleans/2012/04/fertel_tulane_clinic_moves_to.html|title=Fertel Tulane health clinic moves to new home in Mid-City|publisher=Times-Picayune|date=April 25, 2012|accessdate=November 26, 2013}}</ref> In May 2008, Ruth's Chris reopened in New Orleans and is centrally located downtown in [[Harrah's New Orleans|Harrah's Hotel]] at 525 Fulton Street.\n\nIn 2011, the corporate headquarters was relocated to its current location in [[Winter Park, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth's Hospitality Group moving to Winter Park|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2011-07-20/business/os-ruths-hospitality-moving-20110720_1_ruth-s-hospitality-group-mitchell-s-fish-market-headquarters-move|work=Orlando Sentinel, July 20, 2011|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Home Suite Home|url=http://winterparkmag.com/winterparkmag/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1172&Itemid=81|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130412041710/http://winterparkmag.com/winterparkmag/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1172&Itemid=81|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 12, 2013|work=Winter Park Magazine|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Recent expansion and current performance ====\n[[File:Ruth's Hospitality Group logo.jpg|thumb|right|Ruth's Hospitality Group logo]]\nIn February 2008, the company purchased the [[Mitchell's Fish Market|Mitchell's Fish Restaurant]] and Columbus Fish Market brands from [[Cameron Mitchell Restaurants]] for $92 million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth's Chris Completes Acquisition of Mitchell's|url=http://www.seafoodsource.com/newsarticledetail.aspx?id=1336|work=Seafood Source, 20 February 2008|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> As the [[Great Recession|recession]] began to bite, the acquisition was not initially successful. The stock price fell from $22 in 2006 to under $5 and company debts rose to $185 million. CFO Tom Pennison resigned, and CEO [[Craig Miller (CEO)|Craig Miller]] was ousted by the board to be replaced by Mike O'Donnell.<ref>{{cite web|title=GOP Senate hopeful defends moving Ruth's Chris HQ here after Katrina|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2011-09-07/news/os-craig-miller-business-background-20110904_1_ruth-fertel-chris-steak-house-darden-restaurants/2|work=Orlando Sentinel, 7 Sept, 2011|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Former Ruth's Chris CEO Craig Miller joins Republican field for U.S. Senate|url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/national/former-ruths-chris-ceo-craig-miller-joins-republican-field-for-us-senate/1180051|work=Tampa Bay Times|date=July 12, 2011|accessdate=February 19, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129001303/http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/national/former-ruths-chris-ceo-craig-miller-joins-republican-field-for-us-senate/1180051|archivedate=January 29, 2012}}</ref> O'Donnell restructured and rebranded the company, creating [[Ruth's Hospitality Group]] (RHGI) as the parent entity in May 2008, allowing each of the individual restaurant brands to have their own identity within the group. The current President and COO is Kevin Toomy, formerly owner and president of the award-winning Goldcoast Seafood Grill in South Florida.\n\nIn February 2013, RHGI reported that fourth quarter sales at Ruth's Chris restaurants were up by 7.0 percent on the previous year, representing the 11th consecutive quarterly increase in sales.<ref name=\"phx.corporate-ir.net\">{{cite web|title=\nRuth\u2019s Hospitality Group, Inc. Reports Full Year and Fourth Quarter 2012 Financial Results|url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=190038&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1785522&highlight=|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nRuth's Chris continues to add new restaurants, most recently in [[Harrah's Las Vegas|Harrah's]] casino in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] in January 2013, after the previous Las Vegas location on Flamingo closed in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=\nRuth's Chris Rumbles Back into Las Vegas|url=http://vegas.eater.com/archives/2013/01/28/ruths-chris-rumbles-back-into-las-vegas.php|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\nRuth's Chris on Flamingo closing|url=http://www.lvrj.com/news/52756352.html|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal, 8 August 2009|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> The company has announced plans for 2013 that include an expansion into China,{{dl|date=April 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|title=\nRuth's Chris Steak House Expands Global Presence to China|url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=190038&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1779389&highlight=|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}{{dl|date=April 2020}}</ref> a new restaurant in [[Denver]], Colorado, and four or five new franchised locations.<ref name=\"phx.corporate-ir.net\"/> In 2015, it was announced that the restaurant was expanding into [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Jessica Dyer|url=http://www.abqjournal.com/579780/abqnewsseeker/ruths-chris-steak-house-coming-to-albuquerque.html|title=Ruth\u2019s Chris Steak House coming to Albuquerque |publisher=[[Albuquerque Journal]]  |date=May 6, 2015}}</ref> In 2016, Ruth's Chris opened its restaurant in [[Odenton, Maryland]]. In 2018, Ruth's Chris opened its newest restaurant at the [[Silver Legacy Reno|Silver Legacy]] in [[Reno, Nevada]] which replaced Sterling's Seafood Steakhouse that had been in business from 1995 to 2018.\n\n== Lawsuits and discrimination ==\nOn multiple occasions and in several jurisdictions, Ruth's Chris has been the target of legal action for its treatment of staff, employees, and customers. In 2011, class action status was granted to female employees in a complaint that charged the company with pay discrimination, fewer promotions, and maintaining a \"sexually-charged\" environment. <ref name=forbes>{{cite news |last= Casserly |first= Meghan|date=October 19, 2011 |title=Ruth's Chris Hit With Class Action Discrimination Suit |url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/meghancasserly/2011/10/19/ruths-chris-hit-with-class-action-discrimination-suit/#11e9b4ea5a9c|work= Forbes|location= |access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe restaurant chain was sued in 2014 for grave and indelible injuries caused to a customer at a New Orleans branch. Staff failed to warn the customer about an improperly installed threshold.<ref name=lr>{{cite news |last=Partington |first=  Chelsea |date=August 8, 2014 |title= Ruth's Chris Steakhouse sued over patron's injury\n|url=https://louisianarecord.com/stories/510584972-ruth-s-chris-steakhouse-sued-over-patron-s-injury |work= Louisiana Record|location=Louisiana |access-date=August 8, 2019 }}</ref> In 2017, the company was accused of denying service to African-American customers, as part of a class action lawsuit. The charges stemmed from a Houston customer who was seated in a different dining area. <ref name=houstonchron>{{cite news |last= Banks |first=Gabrielle  |date=February 15, 2017 |title= Burger war: Ruth's Chris accused of denying service to African-American in federal lawsuit|url= https://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Ruth-s-Chris-accused-of-denying-service-to-10934729.php|work=Houston Chronicle|location= Houston|access-date=February 15, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== Response to COVID-19 ==\nDuring the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]], [[Ruth's Hospitality Group]] received $20 million in forgivable loans intended for small businesses from the [[Paycheck Protection Program]], leading to widespread backlash.<ref name=wsj>{{cite web |last1=Scott |first1=Charity L. |title=Ruth\u2019s Chris Steak House Gets $20 Million From Coronavirus Aid Program |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/ruths-chris-steak-house-gets-20-million-from-coronavirus-aid-program-11586895864 |website=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> The funds were distributed as part of the government's $2.2 trillion [[Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act|CARES Act]], which set limits of $10 million per entity. On April 17, 2020, two of the company's subsidiaries each received $10 million. <ref name=fox>{{cite web |last1= Genovese |first1= Daniella |title=Ruth's Chris Steak House receives $20M in coronavirus relief |url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/money/coronavirus-relief-ruth-chris-steak-house |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=wsj/> These loans were meant for companies with 500 or less employees while Ruth's Chris employs more than 5,700. <ref name=wsj/> On April 24, 2020, it was reported that the loans would be repaid to the Treasury Department following the public controversy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ktvu.com/news/ruths-chris-steakhouse-owner-to-return-20m-in-small-business-loans|title=Ruth's Chris Steakhouse owner to return $20M in small business loans|date=2020-04-24|website=FOX Business|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\n== Dining ==\n[[File:Ruth's Chris Steak House, Charlotte.jpg|thumb|Ruth's Chris Steak House in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]]]]\nMost restaurants are open for dinner only, although some locations also offer lunch. The [[Dress code#Private dress codes|dress code]] is usually a range from business/dressy to business casual. Most locations have private dining facilities and offer business communications via satellite. The company also offers outside catering and a wedding service through the ''Ruth's Weddings'' brand.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth's Chris Private Dining|url=http://www.ruthschris.com/PrivateDining/|accessdate=February 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth's Weddings|url=http://www.ruthschris.com/Catering/weddings/|accessdate=February 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Menu ===\nThe restaurant's signature is serving [[USDA grade|USDA prime]] steaks that are seared at 1800\u00b0 Fahrenheit<ref>[http://www.ruthschris.com/steak/steak.html Savor Perfection with a Steak from Ruth's Chris Steak House] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630110544/http://www.ruthschris.com/steak/steak.html |date=June 30, 2007 }}, Ruth's Chris Steak House, accessed July 2, 2007.</ref> (approximately 980&nbsp;\u00b0C) and served on ceramic plates heated to 500\u00b0 Fahrenheit (260&nbsp;\u00b0C). Half an ounce (1 [[Tbsp]]) of [[butter]] is added just before the plates leave the kitchen in order to create the signature 'sizzle'. Fertel firmly believed that the success of her steaks was due as much to the sound and smell of the 'sizzle' as well as the taste. \"You hear that sizzle, and you think, 'I wonder if that's my steak'\", she commented in an interview shortly before her death.<ref>Do What You Love (video 2013)</ref>\n\nIn addition to steaks, the restaurant also serves [[entree]]s of [[chicken]], [[Lamb and mutton|lamb]], [[fish]], [[shrimp]] and [[lobster]].<ref name=\"corporate website\">[http://ruthschris.com/menu/entrees.html Sample menu] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070405190230/http://www.ruthschris.com/menu/entrees.html |date=April 5, 2007 }}, ruthschris.com, accessed April 22, 2007.</ref>\n\nPortions generally are large enough to serve two or more diners. Family style side dishes include [[Gratin|au gratin]] [[potatoes]], topped with a [[bechamel sauce]] and [[Cheddar cheese]]. Some recipes, such as the BBQ shrimp, New Orleans-style creamed spinach or the sweet potato [[casserole]], are traditional 19th century [[Louisiana]] recipes that originate with Ruth Fertel's family, particularly her great-uncle Martin, a Louisiana Delta farmer from a [[Alsace|French-Alsatian]] family.<ref>\n{{cite web|title=The origin of Ruth's Chris Creamed Spinach recipe|url=http://www.nola.com/food/index.ssf/2012/11/ruths_chris_creamed_spinach.html|work=The Times-Picayune|date= Nov 30, 2012|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> Some of these recipes have been made publicly available by the family and by the company.<ref>http://pinterest.com/RuthsChrisSteak/ruth-s-recipes/</ref>\n\nAlso available are dessert selections, with the restaurant's signature [[creme brulee]] being a staple item throughout the chain.<ref name=\"corporate website\"/>\n\nIn 2009,<ref>http://chowhound.chow.com/topics/594144</ref> Ruth's Chris introduced their \"Ruth's Classics\" menu of [[prix fixe]] meals where guests choose a three-course meal; starter, entree and side, and dessert. This menu is updated seasonally every three months.<ref>http://www.ruthschris.com/Promotions/ruths-classics/</ref>\n\n=== Beverages ===\n\nThe wine list includes over 200 wines, primarily from leading Californian vineyards such as [[Robert Mondavi|Mondavi]], [[Beringer Vineyards|Beringer]] and [[Stag's Leap Winery|Stag's Leap]]. Twenty-five or more wines are available by the glass, depending on location.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth\u2019s Chris Taps Growth Opportunity With Creative By The Glass Wine Program|url=http://www.shankennewsdaily.com/index.php/2011/07/07/1099/ruths-chris-taps-growth-opportunity-with-creative-by-the-glass-wine-program/|work=Shanken News Daily|date= July 7, 2011|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe seasonal \"vintage-inspired\" cocktail selection, introduced in 2011 by Beverage Director Helen Mackey, includes both classic and contemporary \"hand-crafted\" cocktails.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth\u2019s Chris Steak House Introduces a New Vintage-Inspired Cocktail Program|url=http://www.restaurantmagazine.com/ruths-chris-steak-house-introduces-a-new-vintage-inspired-cocktail-program/|work=Restaurant Magazine|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|www.ruthschris.com}}\n* [http://www.rhgi.com/ Ruth's Hospitality Group, Inc., Official Site]\n* [https://finance.yahoo.com/q/ks?s=RUTH Updated financials from Yahoo! Finance]\n\n[[Category:Steakhouses in the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Orange County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Restaurants established in 1965]]\n[[Category:Madison Dearborn Partners companies]]\n[[Category:Restaurant chains in the United States]]\n[[Category:1965 establishments in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Fine dining]]\n[[Category:Winter Park, Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Ruth's Chris Steak House\n| logo             = Ruths Chris Logo.svg\n| type             = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as        = \n| foundation       = Broad Street, [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]] (1965)\n| location_city    = \n| location_country =\n| location         = [[Winter Park, Florida]]\n| locations        = 100+ [[steakhouse]]s<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=190038&p=irol-homeprofile</ref>\n| founder          = [[Ruth Fertel]]\n| key_people       = Mike O'Donnell ([[Chairman]] & [[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]]), Kevin Toomy ([[Chief Operating Officer]])\n| area_served      = United States <br> Canada <br> Aruba <br> Panama <br> Puerto Rico <br> Mexico <br> Singapore <br> China <br> Indonesia <br> Japan <br> Taiwan <br> Hong Kong\n| industry         = [[Restaurant]]s\n| products         = Food service\n| services         =\n| revenue          = [[United States dollar|US$]]468 million {{small|(FY 2019)}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Darby |first1=Luke |title=Ruth's Chris Made $468 Million in Revenue but Gobbled Up $20 Million in Small Business Relief |url=https://www.gq.com/story/ruths-chris-small-business-steakhouse |work=GQ |date=April 20, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| num_employees    = 5000+ (''2020'')<ref name=wsj/><ref name=\"hoovers.com\">{{cite web|url=http://hoovers.com/company/Ruths_Hospitality_Group_Inc/cthsif-1.html |title=Ruth's Hospitality Group, Inc. &#124; Company profile from Hoover's &#124; 407-333-7440 |publisher=Hoovers.com |date=October 21, 2010 |accessdate=January 25, 2012}}</ref>\n| parent           = [[Ruth's Hospitality Group]]\n| divisions        =\n| subsid           =\n| caption          =\n| homepage         = {{URL|www.ruthschris.com}}\n| dissolved        =\n| footnotes        =\n| intl             =\n}}\n\n'''Ruth's Chris Steak House''' is a chain of over 100 [[steakhouse]]s<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=190038&p=irol-homeprofile</ref> across the [[United States]], Canada and Mexico. On May 22, 2008, the company underwent rebranding and became part of [[Ruth's Hospitality Group]] after its acquisition of [[Mitchell's Fish Market]].<ref>[http://columbus.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2008/03/24/daily28.html?ana=yfcpc Ruth's Chris vying to change name], First of Columbus, March 27, 2008</ref> The group's headquarters are in [[Winter Park, Florida]].<ref>\"[http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/MapItDrawServlet?geo_id=16000US1229320&_bucket_id=50&tree_id=420&context=saff&_lang=en&_sse=on Heathrow CDP, Florida] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606041900/http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/MapItDrawServlet?geo_id=16000US1229320&_bucket_id=50&tree_id=420&context=saff&_lang=en&_sse=on |date=2011-06-06 }}.\" [[U.S. Census Bureau]]. Retrieved on February 26, 2010.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.ruthschris.com/HomeOffice Home Office] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100225054209/http://www.ruthschris.com/HomeOffice |date=2010-02-25 }}.\" Ruth's Hospitality Group. Retrieved on February 26, 2010.</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== The original Chris Steak House (1927\u20131965) ===\nChris Steak House was founded on February 27, 1927 by [[New Orleans]] entrepreneur Chris Matulich.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1998/07/06/244825/index.htm|title=So Just What Does 'Ruth's Chris' Mean?|work=Fortune|accessdate=July 11, 2019|date=July 6, 1998|author=Anne Faircloth}}</ref> It was located at 1100 North Broad Street near the [[Fair Grounds Race Course]], seated 60 people, and had no parking lot. During Matulich's 38-year management, the business was sold six times, failing each time, and enabling him to buy the restaurant back cheaply from the purchasers.<ref>Fortune Magazine, October 2003</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth's Chris Steak House History|url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/ruth-s-chris-steak-house-history/|work=Funding Universe|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Ownership by Ruth Fertel, 1965\u20131999 ===\n\n==== Acquisition, 1965 ====\n\n[[Ruth Fertel]] was a divorced single mother who needed money to send her teenage sons to college. Ignoring the advice of her banker, lawyer, and friends, Ruth purchased the restaurant in 1965.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth Fertel: A Pioneer in the Restaurant Industryauthor= Katie Bloor & Linda J Shea|url=http://people.umass.edu/q4/0%200%20Profiles/20-1%20Ruth%20Fertel%20paper.doc|work=HTM 591S \u2013 Foundations in Hospitality and Tourism Management|publisher=University of Massachusetts Amherst|accessdate=February 4, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402103935/http://people.umass.edu/q4/0%200%20Profiles/20-1%20Ruth%20Fertel%20paper.doc|archivedate=April 2, 2015}}</ref> She used her brother's restaurant, Sig's Antique Restaurant in Port Sulphur, Louisiana, along with family recipes to lay the foundation for her restaurant.<ref>{{cite web|title=The BP Oil Spill and the Bounty of Plaquemines Parish|author= Randy Fertel|url=http://www.gastronomica.org/bp-oil-spill-bounty-plaquemines-parish/|work=Gastronomica The Journal of Critical Food Studies|accessdate=January 2, 2015}}</ref> She initially planned to raise just $18,000 to cover the purchase price, until it was pointed out to her that she would need an additional $4,000 to cover the cost of renovations and food.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steamroller \u2013 Ruth Fertel|url=http://capitalistchicks.com/?q=node/527|work=Capitalist Chicks|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref> On her first day, May 24, 1965, she sold 35 steaks at $5 each.<ref name=\"Her Life Is The Stuff Of Legend\">{{cite web|title=Her Life Is The Stuff Of Legend|url=http://www.fertel.com/images/about_ruth.pdf|accessdate=February 4, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024163101/http://www.fertel.com/images/about_ruth.pdf|archivedate=October 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nFertel personally took a hand in every part of the business. She had to teach herself how to butcher steak, and despite being just five-foot-two and 110-pounds, would saw up 30-pound short loins by hand until she could afford an electric band saw. She staffed her restaurant with single mothers, saying that they were hard workers and reliable. For many years, Chris Steak House was the only upscale restaurant in New Orleans with an all-female wait staff.<ref name=\"Her Life Is The Stuff Of Legend\"/>\n\nFrom the beginning, her restaurant attracted local politicians as well as athletes, businessmen and reporters. Political reporter Rosemary James noted that she \"would not have missed a Friday before a major election at Ruth's Chris Steak House. That was the place to be if you wanted to get some scoops.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Randy Fertel, philanthropist and son of steakhouse founder Ruth and 'Gorilla Man' Rodney puts family's legacy into print|url=http://www.nola.com/dining/index.ssf/2011/10/randy_fertel_philanthropist_an.html|work=The Times-Picayune|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref> Local celebrities like [[Fats Domino]] were regulars.<ref name=\"bluetoad.com\">{{cite web|title=An Author Finds His Therapy Inside A Family Memoir|url=http://www.bluetoad.com/publication/?i=95286&p=38|work=De Soto: Exploring the South|date= January 2012|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Name change to ''Ruth's Chris Steak House'', 1976 ====\n\nIn early 1976, shortly after Fertel signed a new ten-year lease on the restaurant, a fire destroyed the building. Fertel had recently acquired a second property nearby to rent out as a party space. Within seven days, she had relocated the restaurant to its new location a few blocks away at 711 North Broad Street and re-opened it, expanding to 160 seats in the process.<ref name=\"Her Life Is The Stuff Of Legend\"/> The sales agreement with Matulich prevented her from using the original name at any other address, so she named the new restaurant ''Ruth's Chris Steak House'' in order to keep some continuity with the previous location.<ref>McDowell, Bill, \"Ruth's Chris Steak House,\" ''Restaurants & Institutions'', August 1, 1994, 54.</ref> She admitted later to ''Fortune Magazine'' that \"I've always hated the name, but we've always managed to work around it.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth Fertel of Steakhouse Fame Is Dead at 75|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/18/business/ruth-fertel-of-steakhouse-fame-is-dead-at-75.html|work=NY Times|date= April 18, 2002|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Expansion and franchising, 1976\u20131999 ====\nThe first franchised restaurant was opened in 1977 by a loyal customer, [[T. J. Moran|Thomas J. \"T. J.\" Moran]] (c. 1931\u20132015), in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana|Baton Rouge]], who went on to open several more franchised Ruth's Chris locations, TJ Ribs, and Ruffino's restaurants<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theadvocate.com/news/12405583-123/philanthropist-restaurateur-tj-moran-dies|title=Philanthropist, founder of TJ Ribs, Ruffino\u2019s restaurants T.J. Moran dies at age 84, family friend says: Restaurateur funded medical outreach|publisher=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|Baton Rouge Advocate]]|author=Bill Lodge|accessdate=May 19, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150520155406/http://theadvocate.com/news/12405583-123/philanthropist-restaurateur-tj-moran-dies|archivedate=May 20, 2015}}</ref> through his company T.J. Moran Associates. Fertel noted, \"All our franchisees were people who had eaten at one time or another in one of our restaurants. We never looked for franchisees. They came to us.\"<ref name=\"Her Life Is The Stuff Of Legend\"/> The chain expanded rapidly over the next two decades, with 66 locations in the U.S. and overseas by mid-1998,<ref>{{cite web|title=So Just What Does 'Ruth's Chris' Mean?|url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1998/07/06/244825/|work=CNN Money|date=July 6, 1998|accessdate=February 19, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130409095426/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1998/07/06/244825/|archivedate=April 9, 2013}}</ref><ref>\"Never Give Up: Ruth's Chris Steak House,\" ''Entrepreneur Magazine'', September 1997, 81.</ref> and achieving over $200 million in annual revenues.<ref name=\"articles.chicagotribune.com\">{{cite web|title=Madison Dearborn Finds Ruth's Chris To Be Tasty Morsel|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-07-20/business/9907200346_1_madison-dearborn-partners-ruth-fertel-kellogg|work=Chicago Tribune|date= July 20, 1999|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> This success earned Fertel a number of accolades as an entrepreneur, and the [[epithet]] ''The First Lady of American Restaurants'' or ''The Empress of Steak''.<ref name=\"bluetoad.com\"/>\n\n=== Acquisition by Madison Dearborn 1999\u20132005 ===\nIn 1999, Fertel, then 72, developed [[lung cancer]]. She sold a 79.3 percent interest in the chain in August 1999 to investment company [[Madison Dearborn|Madison Dearborn Partners]] of [[Chicago]], remaining as a shareholder until her death in 2002.<ref name=\"articles.chicagotribune.com\"/>\n\nIn that period, the chain expanded to 86 restaurants, including 10 overseas locations. Revenues fell to $167.8 million in 2003, before rising again to $192.2 million in 2004.\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth's Chris IPO to raise $235M|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/tampabay/stories/2005/04/25/daily12.html|work=Tampa Bay Business Journal|date= April 25, 2005|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Public company, 2005 onwards ===\n\nOn August 9, 2005, under President & CEO Craig Miller, Ruth's Chris Steak House became a [[public company]] following a successful [[IPO]] valuing the company at $235 million and an increase of 15 percent in first-day trading.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth's Chris Steak IPO sizzles|url=http://articles.marketwatch.com/2005-08-09/news/30713731_1_stock-market-debut-friedman-billings-renaissance-capital|work=Wall Street Journal|date=August 9, 2005|accessdate=February 19, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130411073426/http://articles.marketwatch.com/2005-08-09/news/30713731_1_stock-market-debut-friedman-billings-renaissance-capital|archivedate=April 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Relocation to Florida, 2005 ====\n\nIn late August 2005 [[Hurricane Katrina]] devastated [[Greater New Orleans]] (see: [[Effect of Hurricane Katrina on New Orleans]]), and  the chain moved its corporate headquarters to [[Heathrow, Florida]]. Like most businesses in the city, two of the chain's locations in the New Orleans area were forced to close because of the storm.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dash |first=Craig |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/09/business/09ruth.html?ex=1283918400&en=eed85083a22295e3&ei=5090&partner=rssuserland&emc=rss|title=Ruth Built the Steakhouse. Katrina Intervened |publisher=New York Times|date=September 5, 2005 |accessdate=April 22, 2007}}</ref> The [[Metairie, Louisiana|Metairie]] location has since reopened.<ref>http://www.ruthschris.com/Restaurant-Locations/metairie</ref> Members of the Fertel family, particularly Ruth's son Randy, were bitterly opposed to the move. Amid much criticism by local officials and media, and on the heels of the announcement by [[Morton's]] that it would reopen its own New Orleans branch,<ref>{{cite news |last=Fitzmorris |first=Tim |url=http://www.neworleanscitybusiness.com/viewStory.cfm?recID=14865 |title=Morton\u2019s beefs up city\u2019s diminished steak offerings |publisher=New Orleans City Business |date=February 27, 2006 |accessdate=April 22, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928075605/http://www.neworleanscitybusiness.com/viewStory.cfm?recID=14865 |archivedate=September 28, 2007 }}</ref> the corporate offices announced that, due to extensive damage, the old flagship location on Broad Street would be permanently closed and donated to charity.<ref>[http://www.ruthschris.com/news/details.php?id=43 Press Release] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061231005420/http://www.ruthschris.com/news/details.php?id=43 |date=December 31, 2006 }}, Ruth's Chris Steakhouse, Inc., November 18, 2005.</ref> [[Tulane University]] was the recipient of the gift, remodeling and reopening the site in 2012 as the Ruth U. Fertel/Tulane Community Health Center.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rickard|first=Mary|url=http://blog.nola.com/new_orleans/2012/04/fertel_tulane_clinic_moves_to.html|title=Fertel Tulane health clinic moves to new home in Mid-City|publisher=Times-Picayune|date=April 25, 2012|accessdate=November 26, 2013}}</ref> In May 2008, Ruth's Chris reopened in New Orleans and is centrally located downtown in [[Harrah's New Orleans|Harrah's Hotel]] at 525 Fulton Street.\n\nIn 2011, the corporate headquarters was relocated to its current location in [[Winter Park, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth's Hospitality Group moving to Winter Park|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2011-07-20/business/os-ruths-hospitality-moving-20110720_1_ruth-s-hospitality-group-mitchell-s-fish-market-headquarters-move|work=Orlando Sentinel, July 20, 2011|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Home Suite Home|url=http://winterparkmag.com/winterparkmag/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1172&Itemid=81|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130412041710/http://winterparkmag.com/winterparkmag/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1172&Itemid=81|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 12, 2013|work=Winter Park Magazine|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Recent expansion and current performance ====\n[[File:Ruth's Hospitality Group logo.jpg|thumb|right|Ruth's Hospitality Group logo]]\nIn February 2008, the company purchased the [[Mitchell's Fish Market|Mitchell's Fish Restaurant]] and Columbus Fish Market brands from [[Cameron Mitchell Restaurants]] for $92 million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth's Chris Completes Acquisition of Mitchell's|url=http://www.seafoodsource.com/newsarticledetail.aspx?id=1336|work=Seafood Source, 20 February 2008|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> As the [[Great Recession|recession]] began to bite, the acquisition was not initially successful. The stock price fell from $22 in 2006 to under $5 and company debts rose to $185 million. CFO Tom Pennison resigned, and CEO [[Craig Miller (CEO)|Craig Miller]] was ousted by the board to be replaced by Mike O'Donnell.<ref>{{cite web|title=GOP Senate hopeful defends moving Ruth's Chris HQ here after Katrina|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2011-09-07/news/os-craig-miller-business-background-20110904_1_ruth-fertel-chris-steak-house-darden-restaurants/2|work=Orlando Sentinel, 7 Sept, 2011|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Former Ruth's Chris CEO Craig Miller joins Republican field for U.S. Senate|url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/national/former-ruths-chris-ceo-craig-miller-joins-republican-field-for-us-senate/1180051|work=Tampa Bay Times|date=July 12, 2011|accessdate=February 19, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129001303/http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/national/former-ruths-chris-ceo-craig-miller-joins-republican-field-for-us-senate/1180051|archivedate=January 29, 2012}}</ref> O'Donnell restructured and rebranded the company, creating [[Ruth's Hospitality Group]] (RHGI) as the parent entity in May 2008, allowing each of the individual restaurant brands to have their own identity within the group. The current President and COO is Kevin Toomy, formerly owner and president of the award-winning Goldcoast Seafood Grill in South Florida.\n\nIn February 2013, RHGI reported that fourth quarter sales at Ruth's Chris restaurants were up by 7.0 percent on the previous year, representing the 11th consecutive quarterly increase in sales.<ref name=\"phx.corporate-ir.net\">{{cite web|title=\nRuth\u2019s Hospitality Group, Inc. Reports Full Year and Fourth Quarter 2012 Financial Results|url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=190038&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1785522&highlight=|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nRuth's Chris continues to add new restaurants, most recently in [[Harrah's Las Vegas|Harrah's]] casino in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] in January 2013, after the previous Las Vegas location on Flamingo closed in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=\nRuth's Chris Rumbles Back into Las Vegas|url=http://vegas.eater.com/archives/2013/01/28/ruths-chris-rumbles-back-into-las-vegas.php|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\nRuth's Chris on Flamingo closing|url=http://www.lvrj.com/news/52756352.html|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal, 8 August 2009|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> The company has announced plans for 2013 that include an expansion into China,{{dl|date=April 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|title=\nRuth's Chris Steak House Expands Global Presence to China|url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=190038&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1779389&highlight=|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}{{dl|date=April 2020}}</ref> a new restaurant in [[Denver]], Colorado, and four or five new franchised locations.<ref name=\"phx.corporate-ir.net\"/> In 2015, it was announced that the restaurant was expanding into [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Jessica Dyer|url=http://www.abqjournal.com/579780/abqnewsseeker/ruths-chris-steak-house-coming-to-albuquerque.html|title=Ruth\u2019s Chris Steak House coming to Albuquerque |publisher=[[Albuquerque Journal]]  |date=May 6, 2015}}</ref> In 2016, Ruth's Chris opened its restaurant in [[Odenton, Maryland]]. In 2018, Ruth's Chris opened its newest restaurant at the [[Silver Legacy Reno|Silver Legacy]] in [[Reno, Nevada]] which replaced Sterling's Seafood Steakhouse that had been in business from 1995 to 2018.\n\n== Lawsuits and discrimination ==\nOn multiple occasions and in several jurisdictions, Ruth's Chris has been the target of legal action for its treatment of staff, employees, and customers. In 2011, class action status was granted to female employees in a complaint that charged the company with pay discrimination, fewer promotions, and maintaining a \"sexually-charged\" environment. <ref name=forbes>{{cite news |last= Casserly |first= Meghan|date=October 19, 2011 |title=Ruth's Chris Hit With Class Action Discrimination Suit |url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/meghancasserly/2011/10/19/ruths-chris-hit-with-class-action-discrimination-suit/#11e9b4ea5a9c|work= Forbes|location= |access-date=October 19, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe restaurant chain was sued in 2014 for grave and indelible injuries caused to a customer at a New Orleans branch. Staff failed to warn the customer about an improperly installed threshold.<ref name=lr>{{cite news |last=Partington |first=  Chelsea |date=August 8, 2014 |title= Ruth's Chris Steakhouse sued over patron's injury\n|url=https://louisianarecord.com/stories/510584972-ruth-s-chris-steakhouse-sued-over-patron-s-injury |work= Louisiana Record|location=Louisiana |access-date=August 8, 2019 }}</ref> In 2017, the company was accused of denying service to African-American customers, as part of a class action lawsuit. The charges stemmed from a Houston customer who was seated in a different dining area. <ref name=houstonchron>{{cite news |last= Banks |first=Gabrielle  |date=February 15, 2017 |title= Burger war: Ruth's Chris accused of denying service to African-American in federal lawsuit|url= https://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Ruth-s-Chris-accused-of-denying-service-to-10934729.php|work=Houston Chronicle|location= Houston|access-date=February 15, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== Response to COVID-19 ==\nDuring the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]], [[Ruth's Hospitality Group]] received $20 million in forgivable loans intended for small businesses from the [[Paycheck Protection Program]], leading to widespread backlash.<ref name=wsj>{{cite web |last1=Scott |first1=Charity L. |title=Ruth\u2019s Chris Steak House Gets $20 Million From Coronavirus Aid Program |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/ruths-chris-steak-house-gets-20-million-from-coronavirus-aid-program-11586895864 |website=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> The funds were distributed as part of the government's $2.2 trillion [[Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act|CARES Act]], which set limits of $10 million per entity. On April 17, 2020, two of the company's subsidiaries each received $10 million. <ref name=fox>{{cite web |last1= Genovese |first1= Daniella |title=Ruth's Chris Steak House receives $20M in coronavirus relief |url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/money/coronavirus-relief-ruth-chris-steak-house |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=wsj/> These loans were meant for companies with 500 or less employees while Ruth's Chris employs more than 5,700. <ref name=wsj/> On the April 24, 2020, it was reported that the loans would be repaid to the Treasury Department following the public controversy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ktvu.com/news/ruths-chris-steakhouse-owner-to-return-20m-in-small-business-loans|title=Ruth's Chris Steakhouse owner to return $20M in small business loans|date=2020-04-24|website=FOX Business|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\n== Dining ==\n[[File:Ruth's Chris Steak House, Charlotte.jpg|thumb|Ruth's Chris Steak House in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]]]]\nMost restaurants are open for dinner only, although some locations also offer lunch. The [[Dress code#Private dress codes|dress code]] is usually a range from business/dressy to business casual. Most locations have private dining facilities and offer business communications via satellite. The company also offers outside catering and a wedding service through the ''Ruth's Weddings'' brand.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth's Chris Private Dining|url=http://www.ruthschris.com/PrivateDining/|accessdate=February 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth's Weddings|url=http://www.ruthschris.com/Catering/weddings/|accessdate=February 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Menu ===\nThe restaurant's signature is serving [[USDA grade|USDA prime]] steaks that are seared at 1800\u00b0 Fahrenheit<ref>[http://www.ruthschris.com/steak/steak.html Savor Perfection with a Steak from Ruth's Chris Steak House] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630110544/http://www.ruthschris.com/steak/steak.html |date=June 30, 2007 }}, Ruth's Chris Steak House, accessed July 2, 2007.</ref> (approximately 980&nbsp;\u00b0C) and served on ceramic plates heated to 500\u00b0 Fahrenheit (260&nbsp;\u00b0C). Half an ounce (1 [[Tbsp]]) of [[butter]] is added just before the plates leave the kitchen in order to create the signature 'sizzle'. Fertel firmly believed that the success of her steaks was due as much to the sound and smell of the 'sizzle' as well as the taste. \"You hear that sizzle, and you think, 'I wonder if that's my steak'\", she commented in an interview shortly before her death.<ref>Do What You Love (video 2013)</ref>\n\nIn addition to steaks, the restaurant also serves [[entree]]s of [[chicken]], [[Lamb and mutton|lamb]], [[fish]], [[shrimp]] and [[lobster]].<ref name=\"corporate website\">[http://ruthschris.com/menu/entrees.html Sample menu] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070405190230/http://www.ruthschris.com/menu/entrees.html |date=April 5, 2007 }}, ruthschris.com, accessed April 22, 2007.</ref>\n\nPortions generally are large enough to serve two or more diners. Family style side dishes include [[Gratin|au gratin]] [[potatoes]], topped with a [[bechamel sauce]] and [[Cheddar cheese]]. Some recipes, such as the BBQ shrimp, New Orleans-style creamed spinach or the sweet potato [[casserole]], are traditional 19th century [[Louisiana]] recipes that originate with Ruth Fertel's family, particularly her great-uncle Martin, a Louisiana Delta farmer from a [[Alsace|French-Alsatian]] family.<ref>\n{{cite web|title=The origin of Ruth's Chris Creamed Spinach recipe|url=http://www.nola.com/food/index.ssf/2012/11/ruths_chris_creamed_spinach.html|work=The Times-Picayune|date= Nov 30, 2012|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> Some of these recipes have been made publicly available by the family and by the company.<ref>http://pinterest.com/RuthsChrisSteak/ruth-s-recipes/</ref>\n\nAlso available are dessert selections, with the restaurant's signature [[creme brulee]] being a staple item throughout the chain.<ref name=\"corporate website\"/>\n\nIn 2009,<ref>http://chowhound.chow.com/topics/594144</ref> Ruth's Chris introduced their \"Ruth's Classics\" menu of [[prix fixe]] meals where guests choose a three-course meal; starter, entree and side, and dessert. This menu is updated seasonally every three months.<ref>http://www.ruthschris.com/Promotions/ruths-classics/</ref>\n\n=== Beverages ===\n\nThe wine list includes over 200 wines, primarily from leading Californian vineyards such as [[Robert Mondavi|Mondavi]], [[Beringer Vineyards|Beringer]] and [[Stag's Leap Winery|Stag's Leap]]. Twenty-five or more wines are available by the glass, depending on location.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth\u2019s Chris Taps Growth Opportunity With Creative By The Glass Wine Program|url=http://www.shankennewsdaily.com/index.php/2011/07/07/1099/ruths-chris-taps-growth-opportunity-with-creative-by-the-glass-wine-program/|work=Shanken News Daily|date= July 7, 2011|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe seasonal \"vintage-inspired\" cocktail selection, introduced in 2011 by Beverage Director Helen Mackey, includes both classic and contemporary \"hand-crafted\" cocktails.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth\u2019s Chris Steak House Introduces a New Vintage-Inspired Cocktail Program|url=http://www.restaurantmagazine.com/ruths-chris-steak-house-introduces-a-new-vintage-inspired-cocktail-program/|work=Restaurant Magazine|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|www.ruthschris.com}}\n* [http://www.rhgi.com/ Ruth's Hospitality Group, Inc., Official Site]\n* [https://finance.yahoo.com/q/ks?s=RUTH Updated financials from Yahoo! Finance]\n\n[[Category:Steakhouses in the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Orange County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Restaurants established in 1965]]\n[[Category:Madison Dearborn Partners companies]]\n[[Category:Restaurant chains in the United States]]\n[[Category:1965 establishments in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Fine dining]]\n[[Category:Winter Park, Florida]]\n", "name_user": "Naypta", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar fix for date format change", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruth%27s_Chris_Steak_House"}
{"title_page": "Hunky Dory", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Hunky Dory\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[David Bowie]]\n| cover        = David Bowie - Hunky Dory.jpg\n| alt          = \n| caption      = CD and UK album cover<br>(The original US album cover bears no title)\n| released     = 17 December 1971\n| recorded     = June \u2013 August 1971\n| venue        = \n| studio       = [[Trident Studios|Trident]], London\n| genre        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Art rock]]\n* [[art pop]]}}\n| length       = 41:50\n| label        = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| producer     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Ken Scott]]\n* [[David Bowie]]\n}}\n| prev_title   = [[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]\n| prev_year    = 1970\n| next_title   = [[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]\n| next_year    = 1972\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Hunky Dory\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Changes (David Bowie song)|Changes]]\" / \"[[Andy Warhol (song)|Andy Warhol]]\n | single1date = 7 January 1972\n | single2     = [[Life on Mars? (song)|Life on Mars?]]\n | single2date = 22 June 1973\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Hunky Dory''''' is the fourth studio album by English singer-songwriter [[David Bowie]], released on 17 December 1971 by [[RCA Records]]. It was his first release through RCA, which would be his label for the next decade. Following the [[hard rock]] sound of ''[[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]'', ''Hunky Dory'' marked a move towards [[art rock]] and [[art pop]] styles. Co-produced by [[Ken Scott]] and Bowie himself, it was recorded in mid-1971 at [[Trident Studios]] in London and featured [[Rick Wakeman]] on piano and the musicians who would later be known as [[the Spiders from Mars]] \u2013 comprising [[Mick Ronson]], [[Trevor Bolder]] and [[Mick Woodmansey]]. The album cover, photographed by Brian Ward in monochrome and re-coloured by Terry Pastor, was influenced by a [[Marlene Dietrich]] photo book that Bowie took with him to the photoshoot.\n\nThe album was initially released to favourable critical and commercial reception but wasn't a major success until the commercial breakthrough of his following album ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]'' (1972). It was supported by the singles \"[[Changes (David Bowie song)|Changes]]\" in 1972 and \"[[Life on Mars (song)|Life on Mars?]]\" in 1973. Retrospectively, ''Hunky Dory'' has received critical acclaim and is regarded as one of Bowie's best works. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' chose it as part of their \"100 best albums of all time\" list in January 2010, with journalist [[Josh Tyrangiel]] praising Bowie's \"earthbound ambition to be a [[Bohemianism|boho]] poet with prodigal style\".<ref name=time /> The album has been reissued multiple times and remastered in 2015 as part of the ''[[Five Years (1969\u20131973)]]'' box set.\n\n== Background ==\nFollowing the completion of his third studio album ''[[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]'' in May 1970, Bowie became less active in both the studio and on stage. This was partly due to challenges that were confronting his new manager [[Tony Defries]], who Bowie hired after firing his old manager [[Kenneth Pitt]] and departing music publisher Essex Music.{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=195\u2013196}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=603}} After hearing Bowie's new single \"[[Holy Holy]]\", Defries signed a contract with Chrysalis but thereafter limited his work with Bowie to focus on other projects, including attempting to sign American singer-songwriter [[Stevie Wonder]] following his contract ending with [[Motown Records]]. Because of this, Bowie, who was devoting himself to songwriting, turned to Chrysalis partner Bob Grace. Grace, according to biographer Nicholas Pegg, had \"courted\" Bowie on \"the strength of 'Holy Holy'\", and subsequently booked time at [[Radio Luxembourg]]'s studios in London for Bowie to record his demos.{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=195\u2013196}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=603}} According to his then-wife [[Angie Bowie|Angela]], Bowie had spent time at Haddon composing songs on piano rather than acoustic guitar, which would \"infuse the flavour of the new album.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=603}} Biographer [[Marc Spitz]] notes that a piano could not fit in his Plaistow Grove bedroom, nor was it suitable for playing in clubs or bus tours with his previous groups. Haddon Hall, however, gave him more of a sense of comfort and permanence, something he had not felt before when composing.{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=159}} Here he composed over three dozen songs, many of which would end up on ''Hunky Dory'' and its follow-up ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]''.{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=156}} Two of these were \"[[Moonage Daydream]]\" and \"[[Hang On to Yourself]]\", which he recorded with his short-lived band [[Arnold Corns]] in February 1971,{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=206\u2013207}} and subsequently re-recorded for ''Ziggy Stardust''.{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=156}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=604}}\n\nIn August 1970, due to his disillusionment with Bowie's lack of enthusiasm during the sessions for ''The Man Who Sold the World'' and his dislike of Defries, bassist and producer [[Tony Visconti]] parted ways with Bowie; it was the last time he would see the artist for three to four years.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=197}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=601}} [[Mick Ronson]] and [[Mick Woodmansey|Woody Woodmansey]], who played guitar and drums, respectively for ''The Man Who Sold the World'', similarly parted ways with Bowie, primarily due to their disgruntlement with the artist on top of not being paid for their performances.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=197}} Visconti would then produce music for glam rock artist [[Marc Bolan]] while Ronson and Woodmansey went to [[Haddon Hall]] in [[Bakewell]], [[Derbyshire]] and formed a short-lived group called Ronno with Benny Marshall of [[The Rats (British band)|the Rats]].{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=601}}{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=214}} \n\nThe first song Bowie wrote and demoed for ''Hunky Dory'' was \"[[Oh! You Pretty Things]]\" in January 1971. After recording a demo at Radio Luxembourg, Bowie gave the tape to Grace, who showed it to [[Peter Noone]] of [[Herman's Hermits]]. Noone decided to record \"Oh! You Pretty Things\" and released it as his debut single later that year.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=604}}{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=202\u2013203}} Noone's version reached number 12 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] in mid-June, with Noone telling ''[[NME]]'': \"My view is that David Bowie is the best writer in Britain at the moment...certainly the best since [[Lennon\u2013McCartney|Lennon and McCartney]].\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=220}}\n\n== Writing and recording ==\nAfter the minimal critical and commercial impact of his Arnold Corns project and leaving Mercury Records, Bowie regrouped in the studio in May 1971 to begin work on his next album.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=606}}{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=216, 218}} Initially, he was joined by Arnold Corns guitarist Mark Pritchett, ''Space Oddity'' drummer [[Terry Cox]] and his former Turquoise colleague Tony Hill. However, he came to the conclusion that he couldn't do the project without Ronson.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=606}} Ronson, who had not talked to Bowie in nine months and had become depressed, was enthusiastic when Bowie contacted him. Woodmansey returned with Ronson, who recruited a new bass player to replace Visconti. He initially suggested [[Rick Kemp]], who Bowie recorded with in the King Bees in the mid-1960s. However, upon meeting Bowie at Haddon Hall to audition, Bowie was dismissive of him and, according to Pegg, some reports say that Defries rejected Kemp on the grounds of his \"receding hairline;\" Kemp would instead join the English folk rock band [[Steeleye Span]].{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=606}} So, Ronson suggested his acquaintance [[Trevor Bolder]], a former hairdresser and piano tuner who had previously seen Bowie live in 1970 and met Ronson at Haddon Hall.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=606}}{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=218}} Upon Bolder's hiring, the trio grouped at Haddon to rehearse some of Bowie's new material, of which included album track \"[[Andy Warhol (song)|Andy Warhol]]\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=606}}\n\n[[File:Ken Scott - 2014-11-14 - Andy Mabbett.JPG|thumb|upright=0.65|alt=Ken Scott in 2014|''Hunky Dory'' was the first production collaboration between Bowie and [[Ken Scott]] ''(pictured in 2014)''.]]\nFollowing the birth of his son [[Duncan Jones|Duncan]], Bowie wrote the song \"[[Kooks (song)|Kooks]]\" as a tribute to him. Also known as 'Zowie', Bowie would tell David Wigg in 1973: \"I got the name [Zowie] from a [[Batman]] comic.\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=218}} On 3 June, Bowie and the Spiders, along with traveled to the BBC's Paris Studios in London to record for [[John Peel]]'s radio show ''In Concert''. They were joined by [[Dana Gillespie]], Mark Pritchett, Geoffrey MacCormack (better known as [[Warren Peace]]) and George Underwood.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=219}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=1,093}} The songs they performed were all originals written by Bowie, apart from a cover of [[Chuck Berry]]'s \"[[Almost Grown (song)|Almost Grown]]\" and [[Ron Davies (songwriter)|Ron Davies]]' \"It Ain't Easy\",{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=219}} which was to be recorded for ''Ziggy Stardust'' a year later.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=1,093}} The performance began with \"[[Queen Bitch]]\" and \"[[Bombers (David Bowie song)|Bombers]]\", which Peel says will both be on the upcoming album, although \"Bombers\" was to replaced by the cover \"Fill Your Heart\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=160}} They also played \"[[The Supermen]]\" from ''The Man Who Sold the World'', \"Looking for a Friend\" (which was sung by Pritchett), \"[[Song for Bob Dylan]]\" (which was sung by Underwood) and \"Andy Warhol\" (which was sung by Gillespie).{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=219}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=1,093}} Although Bowie's backing trio were referred to as \"members of a group called Ronno\", the session would become the first performance with the trio who would become known as [[the Spiders from Mars]] and who would record with him for the next three years.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=218}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=1,093}}<ref name=\"Gallucci UCR\" /> \n\n{{quote box|quote=[''Hunky Dory''] is very much a duo record. We just added bass and drums but it was just like the things we did as a duo. It was very spontaneous \u2013 we hardly did any retakes.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=219}}|source= \u2013 [[Mick Ronson]], 1983|width=20%|align=left|style=padding:8px;}}\nBowie and the Spiders officially started work on the album at [[Trident Studios]] in London on 8 June 1971.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=219}} In Visconti's place as a producer was [[Ken Scott]], who would produce Bowie's next three albums: ''Ziggy Stardust'', ''[[Aladdin Sane]]'' and ''[[Pin Ups]]''.<ref name=\"Gallucci UCR\">{{cite web |last1=Gallucci |first1=Michael |title=Revisiting David Bowie's First Masterpiece 'Hunky Dory' |url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/david-bowie-hunky-dory/ |website=Ultimate Classic Rock |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=17 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920175729/https://ultimateclassicrock.com/david-bowie-hunky-dory/ |archive-date=20 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=234}} Scott's first album as a producer,{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=607}} he was previously an engineer on Bowie's two previous albums, along with [[the Beatles]]' ''[[Magical Mystery Tour]]'' (1967) and [[The Beatles (album)|the \"White Album\"]] (1968) at [[Abbey Road Studios]] and [[George Harrison]]'s ''[[All Things Must Pass]]'' (1970), which featured an acoustic sound that Scott borrowed for ''Hunky Dory''.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=607}}{{sfn|Buckley|2005|pp=93\u201394}} Bowie played multiple demos for Scott and the two would then select which ones would be recorded for the album.{{sfn|Buckley|2005|p=94}} On 8 June, the band recorded \"Song for Bob Dylan\",{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=219}} although according to Pegg this version was scrapped and the real version wasn't recorded until 23 June.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=606}} Recording was done very quickly, with Scott recalling in 1999: \"Almost everything was done in one take.\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=219}} Scott recalled that both himself and the Spiders would think a certain section needs to be rerecorded, whether it be vocals or guitar, but Bowie would say \"No, wait, listen\", and when all parts were played simultaneously that would sound perfect, much to Scott's astonishment.{{sfn|Buckley|2005|p=94}} Bolder described recording with Bowie for the first time as a \"nerve-wracking experience\", saying in 1993: \"When that red light came on in the studio it was, God, in at the deep end of what!\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=219}} Bowie had a much better attitude during the sessions, taking an active role in the album's sound and arrangements, a stark contrast to ''The Man Who Sold the World'', which he was generally dismissive of.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=197}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=607}}\n\nKeyboardist [[Rick Wakeman]], then of the [[Strawbs]] and a noted [[session musician]],{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=607}} plays piano on the album.{{sfn|Buckley|2005|p=93}} Wakeman was asked to play during the album's sessions and accepted. He recalled in 1995 that he met Bowie in late June 1971 at Haddon Hall, where Bowie played him demos of \"Changes\" and \"[[Life on Mars?]]\" in \"their raw brilliance\". He recalled: \"He [played] the finest selection of songs I have ever heard in one sitting in my entire life...I couldn't wait to get into the studio and record them.\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=223}} The piano Wakeman played on the album was an 1898 [[C. Bechstein|Bechstein]] that was the same one used for the Beatles' 1968 song \"[[Hey Jude]]\" and many of [[Elton John]] and [[Harry Nilsson]]'s early records, and would later be used by [[Queen (band)|Queen]] for \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=608}} According to Wakeman, the sessions initially had a rough start, due to the band not learning the songs. He recalled in the Radio 2 documentary ''Golden Years'' and his autobiography ''Say Yes!'' that Bowie had to halt the sessions, telling the musicians off and to come back when they knew the music. Upon returning after a week, Wakeman said: \"the band were hot! They were so good, and the tracks just flowed through.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=608}} However, this account has been disputed by other band members, including Bolder, who told Kevin Cann: \"[That's] rubbish. David would never have told the band off in the studio. Especially as Mick and Woody had already left him once, and everyone was now getting on. The band would not have survived that \u2013 it definitely didn't happen.\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=223}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=608}} Similarly, Scott said: \"I definitely don't remember that, and it's not something I would forget. I would definitely dispute that one.\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=223}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=608}}\n\nWith Wakeman on the line-up, Bowie and the Spiders recorded reconvened at Trident on 9 July and recorded two takes of \"Bombers\" and \"It Ain't Easy\", the latter featuring backing vocals by Dana Gillespie.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=223}} According to Cann, five days later on 14 July, Defries sent a letter to jazz pianist [[Dudley Moore]] asking him to play piano during a session. There is no known record of Moore responding and although the specific song Defries was asking him to play on is unknown, Cann deduces that it was most likely \"Life on Mars?\".{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=223}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=607}} During this day, the group recorded four takes of \"[[Quicksand (David Bowie song)|Quicksand]]\", the final take appeared on the finished album.{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=223\u2013224}} On 18 July, the group spent the day rehearsing and mixing. During the session, Bowie was introduced by Grace to a band known as Chameleon. He gave them his future ''Ziggy Stardust'' track \"[[Star (David Bowie song)|Star]]\", which they recorded their own unreleased version of.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=224}} On 26 July, a seven-hour mixing session took place in order to compile a promotional album for Gem Productions. At this point, the songs \"Oh! You Pretty Things\", \"Eight Line Poem\", \"Kooks\", \"Queen Bitch\" and \"Andy Warhol\" were recorded, although the mixes of \"Eight Line Poem\" and \"Kooks\" on the promotional album were different than the final mixes on ''Hunky Dory''.{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=224\u2013225}} Two takes of \"[[The Bewlay Brothers]]\" were recorded on 30 July, the second take appearing on the final album. It was recorded on a tape that contained rejected versions of \"Song for Bob Dylan\" and \"Fill Your Heart\".{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=225}} On 6 August, the band recorded \"Life on Mars?\" and \"Song for Bob Dylan\", after which the album recording is deemed complete. Ronson guided the recording of \"Life on Mars?\", counting in each take and overdubbed his guitar, strings, Mellotron and Bowie's vocal.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=225}} Cann does not have a recording date for \"Changes\",{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=219\u2013225}} but Doggett writes that it was recorded sometime between June and July.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=140}}\n\n== Music and lyrics ==\n[[File:Rickwakemanmoog.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|alt=Rick Wakeman performing in 2012|The album features piano by keyboardist [[Rick Wakeman]] ''(pictured in 2012)'', whose playing greatly influenced the songs.]]\nAuthor [[Peter Doggett]] describes ''Hunky Dory'' as \"a collective of attractively accessible pop songs, through which Bowie tested out his feelings about the nature of stardom and power.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=11}} Musical biographer David Buckley said of the album: \"Its almost easy-listening status and conventional musical sensibility has detracted from the fact that, lyrically, this record lays down the blueprint for Bowie's future career.\"<ref name=buckstrange1>{{cite book |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |last=Buckley |first=David |year=2000 |origyear=1999 |publisher=Virgin Books |location=London |isbn=0-7535-0457-X |page=112}}</ref> Spitz describes it as a piano-driven record and because of this, it offers more of an inviting and warmer feel, especially when compared to ''Space Oddity'' and ''The Man Who Sold the World''.{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=159}} The opening track, \"[[Changes (David Bowie song)|Changes]]\", focused on the compulsive nature of artistic reinvention (\"Strange fascination, fascinating me/Changes are taking the pace I'm going through\") and distancing oneself from the rock mainstream (\"Look out, you rock 'n' rollers\"). However, the composer also took time to pay tribute to his influences with the tracks \"[[Song for Bob Dylan]]\", \"[[Andy Warhol (David Bowie song)|Andy Warhol]]\" and the [[The Velvet Underground|Velvet Underground]] inspired \"[[Queen Bitch]]\".\n\nFollowing the [[hard rock]] of Bowie's previous album ''The Man Who Sold the World'', ''Hunky Dory'' saw the partial return of the fey pop singer of ''Space Oddity'', with light fare such as \"[[Kooks (song)|Kooks]]\" and the cover \"Fill Your Heart\" sitting alongside heavier material like the [[occult]]-tinged \"[[Quicksand (David Bowie song)|Quicksand]]\" (whose lyric mentions the Golden Dawn (i.e. the [[Hermetic Order of the Golden Dawn]]) and [[Aleister Crowley]]) and the semi-autobiographical \"[[The Bewlay Brothers]]\". Between the two extremes was \"[[Oh! You Pretty Things]]\", whose pop tune hid lyrics, inspired by [[Friedrich Nietzsche|Nietzsche]], predicting the imminent replacement of modern man by \"the [[\u00dcbermensch|Homo Superior]]\", and which has been cited as a direct precursor to \"[[Starman (song)|Starman]]\" from Bowie's next album, ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]''.{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|p=44}}\n\n== Title and artwork ==\nAlthough Bowie generally left naming his albums until last minute, the title, 'Hunky Dory', was announced at the John Peel session.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=606}} It was suggested by Bob Grace of Chrysalis, who got the idea from an [[Esher]] pub landlord and formerly of the [[Royal Air Force]]. He told Peter and Leni Gillman, the authors of ''Alias David Bowie'', that the landlord had an unusual vocabulary that was \"peppered with upper-crust jargon\", using words such as 'prang' and 'whizzo', and phrases such as 'everything's hunky-dory'. Grace told Bowie and he loved it.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|pp=606\u2013607}} Pegg notes that there was a song from 1957 by the American doo-wop band the Guytones also titled \"Hunky Dory\" that may have played a part as well.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=607}} Spitz notes that 'hunky-dory' is an English slang term that means everything is right in the world.{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=156}} The album's sleeve would bear the credit \"Produced by Ken Scott (assisted by the actor)\". The \"actor\" was Bowie himself, whose \"pet conceit\", in the words of ''[[NME]]'' critics [[Roy Carr]] and [[Charles Shaar Murray]], was \"to think of himself as an actor\".{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|pp=7\u201311}}\n\nThe cover artwork was taken by photographer Brian Ward at his [[Heddon Street]] studio,{{sfn|Pegg|2016|pp=610\u2013611}} who was introduced to Bowie by Grace. One idea was for Bowie to dress as an Egyptian Pharoah, partly inspired by the British media's infatuation with the [[British Museum]]'s new [[Tutankhamun]] exhibit.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=610}} Photos of Bowie posing as a sphinx and in a lotus position were taken \u2013 one of them was released as part of the 1990 ''Space Oddity'' reissue \u2013 but the idea was ultimately not chosen. Bowie later recalled: \"We didn't run with it, as they say. Probably a good idea.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=610}} Rather than something extravagant, Bowie opted for a more minimalist image reflecting the album's \"preoccupation with the silver screen.\" Bowie later said: \"I was into Oxford bags, and there are a pair, indeed, on the back of the album. [I was attempting] what I presumed was kind of an [[Evelyn Waugh]] Oxbridge look.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=611}} The final image is a close-up of Bowie looking up into space as he pushes his hair back from his forehead. Originally shot in monochrome, the image was re-coloured by illustrator Terry Pastor, who recently set up the Main Artery design studio in [[Covent Garden]] with George Underwood; Pastor would later design the cover and sleeve for ''Ziggy Stardust''.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=611}} Pegg writes: \"Bowie's decision to use a re-coloured photo suggests a hand-tinted lobby-card from the days of the silent cinema and, simultaneously, Warhol's famous ''[[Marilyn Diptych]]'' screen-prints.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=611}} Robert Dimery, in his book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]'', also notes the influenced of Warhol's ''Dietrich'' prints and writes that Bowie took a photo book that contained multiple ''Dietrich'' prints with him to the photoshoot.<ref>{{cite book |title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die |last=Dimery |first=Robert |year=2005 |publisher=Quintet Publishing |location=London |isbn=978-1-84403-392-8 |page=[https://archive.org/details/1001albumsyoumus0000unse_l0q0/page/254 254] |url=https://archive.org/details/1001albumsyoumus0000unse_l0q0/page/254 }}</ref>\n\n== Release and aftermath ==\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Erlewine AllMusic\">{{cite web|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|title=''Hunky Dory'' \u2013 David Bowie|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/hunky-dory-mw0000189509|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=13 March 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615072909/http://www.allmusic.com/album/hunky-dory-mw0000189509|archive-date=15 June 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n|rev2score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=David Bowie: Hunky Dory|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?ID=3887|work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|issue=47|date=May 2006|accessdate=14 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070823012137/http://www.blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?ID=3887|archivedate=23 August 2007}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n|rev3score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Kot|first=Greg|authorlink=Greg Kot|title=Bowie's Many Faces Are Profiled on Compact Disc|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-06-10/entertainment/9002170173_1_space-oddity-scary-monsters-ziggy-stardust|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=10 June 1990|accessdate=14 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416150839/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-06-10/entertainment/9002170173_1_space-oddity-scary-monsters-ziggy-stardust|archive-date=16 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n|rev4Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|edition=5th concise|year=2011|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin (writer)|isbn=0-85712-595-8|chapter=David Bowie}}</ref>\n|rev5 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n|rev5score = 10/10<ref name=\"Wolk Pitchfork\">{{cite web|last=Wolk|first=Douglas|authorlink=Douglas Wolk|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/21066-five-years-1969-1973/|title=David Bowie: ''Five Years 1969\u20131973''|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=1 October 2015|accessdate=21 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160206231305/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/21066-five-years-1969-1973/|archive-date=6 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev6 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|rev6score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sheffield|first=Rob|authorlink=Rob Sheffield|title=David Bowie: ''Hunky Dory'' (reissue)|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/cd/review.asp?aid=50071&cf=331|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=18 March 1999|accessdate=14 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031003202846/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/cd/review.asp?aid=50071&cf=331|archivedate=3 October 2003}}</ref>\n|rev7 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n|rev7Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Sheffield|first=Rob|authorlink=Rob Sheffield|chapter=David Bowie|title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]|editor1-last=Brackett|editor1-first=Nathan|editor2-last=Hoard|editor2-first=Christian|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|edition=4th|year=2004|pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/97 97\u201399]|isbn=0-7432-0169-8}}</ref>\n|rev8 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n|rev8score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dolan|first=Jon|title=How to Buy: David Bowie|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s5jfV6kXmTEC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA84|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|volume=22|issue=7|date=July 2006|accessdate=14 July 2016|page=84|journal=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002175230/https://books.google.com/books?id=s5jfV6kXmTEC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA84|archive-date=2 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev9 = ''[[Spin Alternative Record Guide]]''\n|rev9score = 9/10{{sfn|Weisbard|Marks|1995|page=55}}\n|rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n|rev10Score = A\u2212<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cg22.php|title=Consumer Guide (22)|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York|date=30 December 1971|accessdate=28 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815194640/http://robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cg22.php|archive-date=15 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\nFollowing the success of Peter Noone's version of \"Oh! You Pretty Things\", Defries sought to extricate Bowie from his contract with [[Mercury Records]], the label that distributed Bowie's previous two albums.{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=195\u2013196}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=603}} Although his contract was to expire in June 1971, Mercury had intended to renew it with improved terms. However, Defries succeeded in forcing Mercury to terminate his contract in May after threatening to deliver a low-quality album.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|pp=605\u2013606}} Defries was then able to pay off Bowie's debts to Mercury through Gem Productions; Mercury then surrendered their copyright on ''[[David Bowie (1969 album)|David Bowie]]'' (1969) and ''The Man Who Sold the World'' (1970).{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=606}} After ending the contract with Mercury, Defries presented the album to multiple labels in the US. [[RCA Records]], stationed in New York City, liked the album and signed Bowie to a three-album deal on 9 September 1971; RCA would be Bowie's label for the rest of the 1970s.{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=195, 227}} \n\n''Hunky Dory'' was released by RCA on 17 December 1971.<ref name=buckstrange1 />{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|p=40}} Supported by the single \"Changes\", the album scored generally favourable reviews and sold reasonably well on its initial release, without being a major success.{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|pp=7\u201311}} ''[[Melody Maker]]'' called it \"the most inventive piece of song-writing to have appeared on record in a considerable time\", while ''[[NME]]'' described it as Bowie \"at his brilliant best\".<ref name=pegg>{{cite book |title=The Complete David Bowie |last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |authorlink=Nicholas Pegg |year=2004 |origyear=2000 |edition= |publisher=Reynolds & Hearn Ltd |location=London |isbn=1-903111-73-0 |pages=265\u201372}}</ref> In the United States, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' opined that \"''Hunky Dory'' not only represents Bowie's most engaging album musically, but also finds him once more writing literally enough to let the listener examine his ideas comfortably, without having to withstand a barrage of seemingly impregnable verbiage before getting at an idea\".<ref name=rs>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/hunky-dory-19720106 |title=Hunky Dory |author=Mendelsohn, John |accessdate=27 October 2014 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110180003/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/hunky-dory-19720106 |archive-date=10 November 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, it was only after the commercial breakthrough of ''Ziggy Stardust'' in mid-1972 that ''Hunky Dory'' became a hit, climbing to number 3 in the UK<ref name=mojo0702>{{cite journal |last=Sheppard |first=David |date=February 2007 |title=60 Years of Bowie |journal=[[Mojo (magazine)|MOJO Classic]] |page=24}}</ref> and remaining on the [[UK Albums Chart|chart]] for 69 weeks.<ref name=\"auto\">*Roberts, David (editor). ''[[British Hit Singles & Albums|The Guinness Book of British Hit Albums]]'', p71. Guinness Publishing Ltd. 7th edition (1996). {{ISBN|0-85112-619-7}}</ref> In 1973, RCA released \"[[Life on Mars?]]\" as a single, which also made number 3 in the UK.<ref name=buckstrange2>{{cite book |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |last=Buckley |first=David |year=2000 |origyear=1999 |publisher=Virgin Books |location=London |isbn=0-7535-0457-X |page=624}}</ref> A reissue returned the album, in January 1981, to the British chart, where it remained for 51 weeks.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] praised the album writing, \"On the surface, [having] such a wide range of styles and sounds would make an album incoherent, but Bowie's improved songwriting and determined sense of style instead made ''Hunky Dory'' a touchstone for reinterpreting pop's traditions into fresh, postmodern pop music.\"<ref name=\"Erlewine AllMusic\" /> In 1998, ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' magazine readers voted ''Hunky Dory'' the 43rd greatest album of all time, while in 2000 the same magazine placed it at number 16 in its list of the 100 Greatest British Albums Ever. It was also voted number 23 in [[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]'s ''[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]'' 3rd Edition (2000)''.'' In 2003, the album was ranked 107th on ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s list of [[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]], and 108 in a 2012 revised list.<ref name=\"RS 500\">{{cite web| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/david-bowie-hunky-dory-172127/| year=2012| title=500 Greatest Albums: ''Hunky Dory'' \u2013 David Bowie| website=[[Rolling Stone]]| accessdate=19 September 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023215941/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/david-bowie-hunky-dory-172127/| archive-date=23 October 2019| url-status=live}}</ref> In the same year, [[VH1]] placed it 47th and the Virgin [[All Time Top 1000 Albums]] chart placed it at number 16. In 2004, it was ranked 80th on ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''<nowiki/>'s Top 100 Albums of the 1970s. In 2006, ''[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]'' magazine chose it as one of the 100 best albums of all time.<ref name=time>{{cite magazine|author=[[Josh Tyrangiel]]|author2=[[Alan Light]]|title=The All-TIME 100 Albums|accessdate=7 July 2014|date=26 January 2010|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]|url=http://www.time.com/time/2006/100albums/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109195005/http://www.time.com/time/2006/100albums/index.html|archive-date=9 November 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> According to [[Acclaimed Music]], it is the 70th most celebrated album in popular music history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/album/A214.htm|title=Hunky Dory ranked 70th most celebrated album|work=Acclaimed Music|access-date=15 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811085236/http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/album/A214.htm|archive-date=11 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBowie himself considered the album to be one of the most important in his career. Speaking in 1999, he said: \"''Hunky Dory'' gave me a fabulous groundswell. I guess it provided me, for the first time in my life, with an actual audience \u2013 I mean, people actually coming up to me and saying, 'Good album, good songs.' That hadn't happened to me before. It was like, 'Ah, I'm getting it, I'm finding my feet. I'm starting to communicate what I want to do. Now: what is it I want to do?' There was always a double whammy there.\"<ref>Chris Roberts interview with David Bowie in ''Uncut'', October 1999, Issue 29.</ref> Spitz writes that many artists have their \"it all came together on this one\" record, naming the likes of ''[[Beggars Banquet]]'' by [[the Rolling Stones]], ''[[Damn the Torpedoes (album)|Damn the Torpedoes]]'' by [[Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers]], ''[[War (U2 album)|War]]'' by [[U2]] and ''[[The Bends (album)|The Bends]]'' by [[Radiohead]]. \"For David Bowie, it's ''Hunky Dory''.\"{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=158}}\n\n== Track listing ==\nAll tracks written by [[David Bowie]], except where noted.<ref name=\"liner notes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=Hunky Dory|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1971|publisher=[[RCA Records]]|location=UK|type=liner notes|id=SF 8244}}</ref>\n\n;Side one\n# \"[[Changes (David Bowie song)|Changes]]\" \u2013 3:37\n# \"[[Oh! You Pretty Things]]\" \u2013 3:12\n# \"Eight Line Poem\" \u2013 2:55\n# \"[[Life on Mars (song)|Life on Mars?]]\" \u2013 3:43\n# \"[[Kooks (song)|Kooks]]\" \u2013 2:53\n# \"[[Quicksand (David Bowie song)|Quicksand]]\" \u2013 5:08\n\n;Side two\n# \"Fill Your Heart\" ([[Biff Rose]], [[Paul Williams (songwriter)|Paul Williams]]) \u2013 3:07\n# \"[[Andy Warhol (song)|Andy Warhol]]\" \u2013 3:56\n# \"[[Song for Bob Dylan]]\" \u2013 4:12\n# \"[[Queen Bitch]]\" \u2013 3:18\n# \"[[The Bewlay Brothers]]\" \u2013 5:22\n\n* Sides one and two were combined as tracks 1\u201311 on CD reissues.\n\n== CD releases ==\n\n=== 1980s and 1990s ===\n\nFollowing its initial release on compact disc in the mid-1980s, ''Hunky Dory'' was re-released in CD format in 1990, by [[Rykodisc]]/[[EMI]], with bonus tracks.<ref>{{Cite AV media notes|title=Hunky Dory|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1990|publisher=[[EMI]]/Rykodisc|location=UK|type=liner notes|id=EMC 3572}}</ref>\n\n;Bonus tracks (1990 Rykodisc)\n# \"[[Bombers (David Bowie song)|Bombers]]\" (Previously unreleased track, recorded in 1971, mixed 1990; there is a very rare LP sampler issued by RCA prior to the release of the album with the GEM logo on the cover and \"Bombers\" appears followed by the linking cross talk that leads into \"Andy Warhol,\" clearly indicating that Bowie had originally intended it to be the opening track on the second side [instead of \"Fill Your Heart\"]) \u2013 2:38\n# \"[[The Supermen]]\" (Alternate version recorded on 12 November 1971 during sessions for ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]'', originally released on ''[[Glastonbury Fayre (album)|Revelations \u2013 A Musical Anthology for Glastonbury Fayre]]'' in July 1972, compiled by the organisers of the [[Glastonbury Festival]] at which Bowie had played in 1971<ref name=ZSCChanges2>{{cite web |url=http://www.5years.com/ziggy30th2cd.htm |title=EMI 30th Anniversary 2CD Limited Edition (2002) |work=The Ziggy Stardust Companion |accessdate=22 June 2008 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/66YQHIclR?url=http://www.5years.com/ziggy30th2cd.htm |archive-date=30 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>) \u2013 2:41\n# \"Quicksand\" (Demo version, recorded in 1971, mixed 1990) \u2013 4:43\n# \"The Bewlay Brothers\" (Alternate mix) \u2013 5:19\n\nIn 1999, the album was reissued by Virgin/EMI (7243 521899 0 8), without bonus tracks, but with 24-bit digitally remastered sound. This edition was re-pressed in 2014 by Parlophone/Warner Music Group, having acquired the Virgin-owned Bowie catalogue.\n\n=== 2015 remaster ===\n\nIn 2015, the album was remastered for the ''[[Five Years (1969\u20131973)]]'' [[box set]].<ref>[http://www.davidbowie.com/news/five-years-1969-1973-box-set-due-september-54571 FIVE YEARS 1969 \u2013 1973 box set due September] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160218235114/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/five-years-1969-1973-box-set-due-september-54571 |date=18 February 2016 }} at davidbowie.com</ref> It was released in CD, vinyl, and digital formats, both as part of this compilation and separately.<ref>[http://www.superdeluxeedition.com/news/david-bowie-five-years-vinyl-available-separately-next-month David Bowie / 'Five Years' vinyl available separately next month] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216222656/http://www.superdeluxeedition.com/news/david-bowie-five-years-vinyl-available-separately-next-month |date=16 February 2016 }} at superdeluxeedition.com</ref>\n\n== Personnel ==\nAlbum credits per [[Nicholas Pegg]].{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=603}}\n*[[David Bowie]] \u2013 vocals, guitar, [[alto saxophone|alto]] and [[tenor saxophone]], piano (in \"Oh! You Pretty Things\" (together with Rick Wakeman<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uncut.co.uk/news/rick-wakeman-reveals-played-piano-david-bowies-oh-pretty-things-98931|title=Rick Wakeman reveals he played piano on David Bowie's \"Oh! You Pretty Things\" - Uncut|author=|date=17 January 2017|website=uncut.co.uk|access-date=17 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118144242/http://www.uncut.co.uk/news/rick-wakeman-reveals-played-piano-david-bowies-oh-pretty-things-98931|archive-date=18 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/entertainment-arts-38627868/david-bowie-song-question-answered-by-rick-wakeman|title=Bowie or Wakeman piano mystery|author=|date=17 May 2018|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com|access-date=21 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721193608/https://www.bbc.com/news/av/entertainment-arts-38627868/david-bowie-song-question-answered-by-rick-wakeman|archive-date=21 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>), \"Eight Line Poem\" and \"The Bewlay Brothers\")\n*[[Mick Ronson]] \u2013 guitar, vocals, [[Mellotron]], arrangements\n*[[Trevor Bolder]] \u2013 bass guitar, trumpet\n*[[Mick Woodmansey]] \u2013 drums\n*[[Rick Wakeman]] \u2013 piano\n\n'''Production'''\n*[[Ken Scott]] \u2013 producer, [[recording engineer]], [[audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing engineer]]\n*David Bowie \u2013 producer\n*Dr. Toby Mountain \u2013 [[audio mastering|remastering engineer]] (for Rykodisc release)\n*Jonathan Wyner \u2013 assistant remastering engineer, mixing engineer (for Rykodisc release)\n*[[Peter Mew]] \u2013 remastering engineer (for EMI release)\n*Nigel Reeve \u2013 assistant remastering engineer (for EMI release)\n*[[George Underwood (artist)|George Underwood]] \u2013 cover art\n\n== Charts ==\n'''Album'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Chart\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|1972\n|[[UK Albums Chart]]<ref name=ukt40>{{cite web|url=http://www.everyhit.com |title=UK Top 40 Hit Database |accessdate=23 June 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080319091720/http://everyhit.com/ |archivedate=19 March 2008 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|1972\n|Norwegian Albums Chart\n|align=\"center\"|33\n|-\n|1972\n|Australian Albums Chart\n|align=\"center\"|39\n|-\n|2016\n|New Zealand Albums Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/albums?chart=4190|title=The Official New Zealand Music Chart|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122121614/http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/albums?chart=4190|archive-date=22 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|30\n|-\n|2016\n|US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=allmusicalbumcharts>{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r2480|pure_url=yes}} |title=(((Hunky Dory > Charts & Awards > Billboard Albums))) |accessdate=23 June 2008 |work=AllMusic}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|57\n|-\n|2016\n{{albumchart|BillboardCatalog|4|artist=David Bowie|accessdate=30 January 2016}}\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Single'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Single\n!Chart\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|1972\n|\"Changes\"\n|[[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=allmusicsinglescharts>{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r2480|pure_url=yes}} |title=(((Hunky Dory > Charts & Awards > Billboard Singles))) |accessdate=23 June 2008 |work=Allmusic}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|66\n|-\n|1973\n|\"Life on Mars?\"\n|[[UK Singles Chart]]<ref name=ukt40 />\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|1975\n|\"Changes\"\n|''Billboard'' Pop Singles<ref name=allmusicsinglescharts />\n|align=\"center\"|41\n|}\n\n== Certifications ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n!Organization\n!Level\n!Date\n|-\n|[[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]] \u2013 UK\n|Gold\n|{{start date|df=yes|1982|1|25}}<ref name=bpi>{{cite web |url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/ |title=BPI Certified Awards |accessdate=23 June 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318142521/https://www.bpi.co.uk/ |archive-date=18 March 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n|BPI \u2013 UK\n|Platinum\n|{{start date|df=yes|1982|1|25}}<ref name=bpi />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n;Sources\n*{{cite book |last=Buckley |first=David |year=2005 |origyear=1999 |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |location=London |publisher=Virgin |isbn=978-0-75351-002-5 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Cann |first=Kevin |year=2010 |title=Any Day Now \u2013 David Bowie: The London Years: 1947\u20131974 |publisher=Adelita |isbn=978-0-95520-177-6 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Carr |first1=Roy|authorlink1=Roy Carr |last2=Murray |first2=Charles Shaar| authorlink2=Charles Shaar Murray |year=1981 |title=Bowie: An Illustrated Record |publisher=Eel Pie Pub |isbn=978-0-38077-966-6|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Doggett |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Doggett |year=2012 |title=The Man Who Sold the World: David Bowie and the 1970s |publisher=[[HarperCollins|HarperCollins Publishers]] |isbn=978-0-06-202466-4 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |title=The Complete David Bowie |publisher=[[Titan Books]] |edition=7th |location=London |year=2016 |isbn=978-1-78565-365-0 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Spitz |first=Marc |author-link1=Marc Spitz |title=Bowie: A Biography |publisher=[[Crown Publishing Group]] |year=2009  |isbn=978-0-307-71699-6|title-link=Bowie: A Biography |location=New York |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Weisbard |editor1-first=Eric |editor2-last=Marks |editor2-first=Craig |title=[[Spin Alternative Record Guide]] |publisher=[[Vintage Books]] |year=1995 |isbn=0-679-75574-8 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{David Bowie}}\n\n[[Category:David Bowie albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Ken Scott]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Trident Studios]]\n[[Category:EMI Records albums]]\n[[Category:RCA Records albums]]\n[[Category:1971 albums]]\n[[Category:Rykodisc albums]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records albums]]\n[[Category:Parlophone albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Hunky Dory\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[David Bowie]]\n| cover        = David Bowie - Hunky Dory.jpg\n| alt          = \n| caption      = CD and UK album cover<br>(The original US album cover bears no title)\n| released     = 17 December 1971\n| recorded     = June \u2013 August 1971\n| venue        = \n| studio       = [[Trident Studios|Trident]], London\n| genre        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Art rock]]\n* [[art pop]]}}\n| length       = 41:50\n| label        = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| producer     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Ken Scott]]\n* [[David Bowie]]\n}}\n| prev_title   = [[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]\n| prev_year    = 1970\n| next_title   = [[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]\n| next_year    = 1972\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Hunky Dory\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Changes (David Bowie song)|Changes]]\" / \"[[Andy Warhol (song)|Andy Warhol]]\n | single1date = 7 January 1972\n | single2     = [[Life on Mars? (song)|Life on Mars?]]\n | single2date = 22 June 1973\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Hunky Dory''''' is the fourth studio album by English singer-songwriter [[David Bowie]], released on 17 December 1971 by [[RCA Records]]. It was his first release through RCA, which would be his label for the next decade. Following the [[hard rock]] sound of ''[[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]'', ''Hunky Dory'' marked a move towards [[art rock]] and [[art pop]] styles. Co-produced by [[Ken Scott]] and Bowie himself, it was recorded in mid-1971 at [[Trident Studios]] in London and featured [[Rick Wakeman]] on piano and the musicians who would later be known as [[the Spiders from Mars]] \u2013 comprising [[Mick Ronson]], [[Trevor Bolder]] and [[Mick Woodmansey]]. The album cover, photographed by Brian Ward in monochrome and re-coloured by Terry Pastor, was influenced by a [[Marlene Dietrich]] photo book that Bowie took with him to the photoshoot.\n\nThe album was initially released to favourable critical and commercial reception but wasn't a major success until the commercial breakthrough of his following album ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]'' (1972). It was supported by the singles \"[[Changes (David Bowie song)|Changes]]\" in 1972 and \"[[Life on Mars (song)|Life on Mars?]]\" in 1973. Retrospectively, ''Hunky Dory'' has received critical acclaim and is regarded as one of Bowie's best works. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' chose it as part of their \"100 best albums of all time\" list in January 2010, with journalist [[Josh Tyrangiel]] praising Bowie's \"earthbound ambition to be a [[Bohemianism|boho]] poet with prodigal style\".<ref name=time /> The album has been reissued multiple times and remastered in 2015 as part of the ''[[Five Years (1969\u20131973)]]'' box set.\n\n== Background ==\nFollowing the completion of his third studio album ''[[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]'' in May 1970, Bowie became less active in both the studio and on stage. This was partly due to challenges that were confronting his new manager [[Tony Defries]], who Bowie hired after firing his old manager [[Kenneth Pitt]] and departing music publisher Essex Music.{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=195\u2013196}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=603}} After hearing Bowie's new single \"[[Holy Holy]]\", Defries signed a contract with Chrysalis but thereafter limited his work with Bowie to focus on other projects, including attempting to sign American singer-songwriter [[Stevie Wonder]] following his contract ending with [[Motown Records]]. Because of this, Bowie, who was devoting himself to songwriting, turned to Chrysalis partner Bob Grace. Grace, according to biographer Nicholas Pegg, had \"courted\" Bowie on \"the strength of 'Holy Holy'\", and subsequently booked time at [[Radio Luxembourg]]'s studios in London for Bowie to record his demos.{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=195\u2013196}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=603}} According to his then-wife [[Angie Bowie|Angela]], Bowie had spent time at Haddon composing songs on piano rather than acoustic guitar, which would \"infuse the flavour of the new album.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=603}} Biographer [[Marc Spitz]] notes that a piano could not fit in in Plaistow Grove bedroom, nor was it suitable for playing in clubs or bus tours with his previous groups. Haddon Hall, however, gave him more of a sense of comfort and permanence, something he had not felt before when composing.{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=159}} Here he composed over three dozen songs, many of which would end up on ''Hunky Dory'' and its follow-up ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]''.{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=156}} Two of these were \"[[Moonage Daydream]]\" and \"[[Hang On to Yourself]]\", which he recorded with his short-lived band [[Arnold Corns]] in February 1971,{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=206\u2013207}} and subsequently re-recorded for ''Ziggy Stardust''.{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=156}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=604}}\n\nIn August 1970, due to his disillusionment with Bowie's lack of enthusiasm during the sessions for ''The Man Who Sold the World'' and his dislike of Defries, bassist and producer [[Tony Visconti]] parted ways with Bowie; it was the last time he would see the artist for three to four years.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=197}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=601}} [[Mick Ronson]] and [[Mick Woodmansey|Woody Woodmansey]], who played guitar and drums, respectively for ''The Man Who Sold the World'', similarly parted ways with Bowie, primarily due to their disgruntlement with the artist on top of not being paid for their performances.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=197}} Visconti would then produce music for glam rock artist [[Marc Bolan]] while Ronson and Woodmansey went to [[Haddon Hall]] in [[Bakewell]], [[Derbyshire]] and formed a short-lived group called Ronno with Benny Marshall of [[The Rats (British band)|the Rats]].{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=601}}{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=214}} \n\nThe first song Bowie wrote and demoed for ''Hunky Dory'' was \"[[Oh! You Pretty Things]]\" in January 1971. After recording a demo at Radio Luxembourg, Bowie gave the tape to Grace, who showed it to [[Peter Noone]] of [[Herman's Hermits]]. Noone decided to record \"Oh! You Pretty Things\" and released it as his debut single later that year.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=604}}{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=202\u2013203}} Noone's version reached number 12 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] in mid-June, with Noone telling ''[[NME]]'': \"My view is that David Bowie is the best writer in Britain at the moment...certainly the best since [[Lennon\u2013McCartney|Lennon and McCartney]].\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=220}}\n\n== Writing and recording ==\nAfter the minimal critical and commercial impact of his Arnold Corns project and leaving Mercury Records, Bowie regrouped in the studio in May 1971 to begin work on his next album.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=606}}{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=216, 218}} Initially, he was joined by Arnold Corns guitarist Mark Pritchett, ''Space Oddity'' drummer [[Terry Cox]] and his former Turquoise colleague Tony Hill. However, he came to the conclusion that he couldn't do the project without Ronson.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=606}} Ronson, who had not talked to Bowie in nine months and had become depressed, was enthusiastic when Bowie contacted him. Woodmansey returned with Ronson, who recruited a new bass player to replace Visconti. He initially suggested [[Rick Kemp]], who Bowie recorded with in the King Bees in the mid-1960s. However, upon meeting Bowie at Haddon Hall to audition, Bowie was dismissive of him and, according to Pegg, some reports say that Defries rejected Kemp on the grounds of his \"receding hairline;\" Kemp would instead join the English folk rock band [[Steeleye Span]].{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=606}} So, Ronson suggested his acquaintance [[Trevor Bolder]], a former hairdresser and piano tuner who had previously seen Bowie live in 1970 and met Ronson at Haddon Hall.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=606}}{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=218}} Upon Bolder's hiring, the trio grouped at Haddon to rehearse some of Bowie's new material, of which included album track \"[[Andy Warhol (song)|Andy Warhol]]\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=606}}\n\n[[File:Ken Scott - 2014-11-14 - Andy Mabbett.JPG|thumb|upright=0.65|alt=Ken Scott in 2014|''Hunky Dory'' was the first production collaboration between Bowie and [[Ken Scott]] ''(pictured in 2014)''.]]\nFollowing the birth of his son [[Duncan Jones|Duncan]], Bowie wrote the song \"[[Kooks (song)|Kooks]]\" as a tribute to him. Also known as 'Zowie', Bowie would tell David Wigg in 1973: \"I got the name [Zowie] from a [[Batman]] comic.\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=218}} On 3 June, Bowie and the Spiders, along with traveled to the BBC's Paris Studios in London to record for [[John Peel]]'s radio show ''In Concert''. They were joined by [[Dana Gillespie]], Mark Pritchett, Geoffrey MacCormack (better known as [[Warren Peace]]) and George Underwood.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=219}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=1,093}} The songs they performed were all originals written by Bowie, apart from a cover of [[Chuck Berry]]'s \"[[Almost Grown (song)|Almost Grown]]\" and [[Ron Davies (songwriter)|Ron Davies]]' \"It Ain't Easy\",{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=219}} which was to be recorded for ''Ziggy Stardust'' a year later.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=1,093}} The performance began with \"[[Queen Bitch]]\" and \"[[Bombers (David Bowie song)|Bombers]]\", which Peel says will both be on the upcoming album, although \"Bombers\" was to replaced by the cover \"Fill Your Heart\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=160}} They also played \"[[The Supermen]]\" from ''The Man Who Sold the World'', \"Looking for a Friend\" (which was sung by Pritchett), \"[[Song for Bob Dylan]]\" (which was sung by Underwood) and \"Andy Warhol\" (which was sung by Gillespie).{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=219}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=1,093}} Although Bowie's backing trio were referred to as \"members of a group called Ronno\", the session would become the first performance with the trio who would become known as [[the Spiders from Mars]] and who would record with him for the next three years.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=218}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=1,093}}<ref name=\"Gallucci UCR\" /> \n\n{{quote box|quote=[''Hunky Dory''] is very much a duo record. We just added bass and drums but it was just like the things we did as a duo. It was very spontaneous \u2013 we hardly did any retakes.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=219}}|source= \u2013 [[Mick Ronson]], 1983|width=20%|align=left|style=padding:8px;}}\nBowie and the Spiders officially started work on the album at [[Trident Studios]] in London on 8 June 1971.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=219}} In Visconti's place as a producer was [[Ken Scott]], who would produce Bowie's next three albums: ''Ziggy Stardust'', ''[[Aladdin Sane]]'' and ''[[Pin Ups]]''.<ref name=\"Gallucci UCR\">{{cite web |last1=Gallucci |first1=Michael |title=Revisiting David Bowie's First Masterpiece 'Hunky Dory' |url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/david-bowie-hunky-dory/ |website=Ultimate Classic Rock |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=17 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920175729/https://ultimateclassicrock.com/david-bowie-hunky-dory/ |archive-date=20 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=234}} Scott's first album as a producer,{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=607}} he was previously an engineer on Bowie's two previous albums, along with [[the Beatles]]' ''[[Magical Mystery Tour]]'' (1967) and [[The Beatles (album)|the \"White Album\"]] (1968) at [[Abbey Road Studios]] and [[George Harrison]]'s ''[[All Things Must Pass]]'' (1970), which featured an acoustic sound that Scott borrowed for ''Hunky Dory''.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=607}}{{sfn|Buckley|2005|pp=93\u201394}} Bowie played multiple demos for Scott and the two would then select which ones would be recorded for the album.{{sfn|Buckley|2005|p=94}} On 8 June, the band recorded \"Song for Bob Dylan\",{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=219}} although according to Pegg this version was scrapped and the real version wasn't recorded until 23 June.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=606}} Recording was done very quickly, with Scott recalling in 1999: \"Almost everything was done in one take.\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=219}} Scott recalled that both himself and the Spiders would think a certain section needs to be rerecorded, whether it be vocals or guitar, but Bowie would say \"No, wait, listen\", and when all parts were played simultaneously that would sound perfect, much to Scott's astonishment.{{sfn|Buckley|2005|p=94}} Bolder described recording with Bowie for the first time as a \"nerve-wracking experience\", saying in 1993: \"When that red light came on in the studio it was, God, in at the deep end of what!\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=219}} Bowie had a much better attitude during the sessions, taking an active role in the album's sound and arrangements, a stark contrast to ''The Man Who Sold the World'', which he was generally dismissive of.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=197}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=607}}\n\nKeyboardist [[Rick Wakeman]], then of the [[Strawbs]] and a noted [[session musician]],{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=607}} plays piano on the album.{{sfn|Buckley|2005|p=93}} Wakeman was asked to play during the album's sessions and accepted. He recalled in 1995 that he met Bowie in late June 1971 at Haddon Hall, where Bowie played him demos of \"Changes\" and \"[[Life on Mars?]]\" in \"their raw brilliance\". He recalled: \"He [played] the finest selection of songs I have ever heard in one sitting in my entire life...I couldn't wait to get into the studio and record them.\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=223}} The piano Wakeman played on the album was an 1898 [[C. Bechstein|Bechstein]] that was the same one used for the Beatles' 1968 song \"[[Hey Jude]]\" and many of [[Elton John]] and [[Harry Nilsson]]'s early records, and would later be used by [[Queen (band)|Queen]] for \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=608}} According to Wakeman, the sessions initially had a rough start, due to the band not learning the songs. He recalled in the Radio 2 documentary ''Golden Years'' and his autobiography ''Say Yes!'' that Bowie had to halt the sessions, telling the musicians off and to come back when they knew the music. Upon returning after a week, Wakeman said: \"the band were hot! They were so good, and the tracks just flowed through.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=608}} However, this account has been disputed by other band members, including Bolder, who told Kevin Cann: \"[That's] rubbish. David would never have told the band off in the studio. Especially as Mick and Woody had already left him once, and everyone was now getting on. The band would not have survived that \u2013 it definitely didn't happen.\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=223}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=608}} Similarly, Scott said: \"I definitely don't remember that, and it's not something I would forget. I would definitely dispute that one.\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=223}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=608}}\n\nWith Wakeman on the line-up, Bowie and the Spiders recorded reconvened at Trident on 9 July and recorded two takes of \"Bombers\" and \"It Ain't Easy\", the latter featuring backing vocals by Dana Gillespie.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=223}} According to Cann, five days later on 14 July, Defries sent a letter to jazz pianist [[Dudley Moore]] asking him to play piano during a session. There is no known record of Moore responding and although the specific song Defries was asking him to play on is unknown, Cann deduces that it was most likely \"Life on Mars?\".{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=223}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=607}} During this day, the group recorded four takes of \"[[Quicksand (David Bowie song)|Quicksand]]\", the final take appeared on the finished album.{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=223\u2013224}} On 18 July, the group spent the day rehearsing and mixing. During the session, Bowie was introduced by Grace to a band known as Chameleon. He gave them his future ''Ziggy Stardust'' track \"[[Star (David Bowie song)|Star]]\", which they recorded their own unreleased version of.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=224}} On 26 July, a seven-hour mixing session took place in order to compile a promotional album for Gem Productions. At this point, the songs \"Oh! You Pretty Things\", \"Eight Line Poem\", \"Kooks\", \"Queen Bitch\" and \"Andy Warhol\" were recorded, although the mixes of \"Eight Line Poem\" and \"Kooks\" on the promotional album were different than the final mixes on ''Hunky Dory''.{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=224\u2013225}} Two takes of \"[[The Bewlay Brothers]]\" were recorded on 30 July, the second take appearing on the final album. It was recorded on a tape that contained rejected versions of \"Song for Bob Dylan\" and \"Fill Your Heart\".{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=225}} On 6 August, the band recorded \"Life on Mars?\" and \"Song for Bob Dylan\", after which the album recording is deemed complete. Ronson guided the recording of \"Life on Mars?\", counting in each take and overdubbed his guitar, strings, Mellotron and Bowie's vocal.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=225}} Cann does not have a recording date for \"Changes\",{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=219\u2013225}} but Doggett writes that it was recorded sometime between June and July.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=140}}\n\n== Music and lyrics ==\n[[File:Rickwakemanmoog.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|alt=Rick Wakeman performing in 2012|The album features piano by keyboardist [[Rick Wakeman]] ''(pictured in 2012)'', whose playing greatly influenced the songs.]]\nAuthor [[Peter Doggett]] describes ''Hunky Dory'' as \"a collective of attractively accessible pop songs, through which Bowie tested out his feelings about the nature of stardom and power.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=11}} Musical biographer David Buckley said of the album: \"Its almost easy-listening status and conventional musical sensibility has detracted from the fact that, lyrically, this record lays down the blueprint for Bowie's future career.\"<ref name=buckstrange1>{{cite book |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |last=Buckley |first=David |year=2000 |origyear=1999 |publisher=Virgin Books |location=London |isbn=0-7535-0457-X |page=112}}</ref> Spitz describes it as a piano-driven record and because of this, it offers more of an inviting and warmer feel, especially when compared to ''Space Oddity'' and ''The Man Who Sold the World''.{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=159}} The opening track, \"[[Changes (David Bowie song)|Changes]]\", focused on the compulsive nature of artistic reinvention (\"Strange fascination, fascinating me/Changes are taking the pace I'm going through\") and distancing oneself from the rock mainstream (\"Look out, you rock 'n' rollers\"). However, the composer also took time to pay tribute to his influences with the tracks \"[[Song for Bob Dylan]]\", \"[[Andy Warhol (David Bowie song)|Andy Warhol]]\" and the [[The Velvet Underground|Velvet Underground]] inspired \"[[Queen Bitch]]\".\n\nFollowing the [[hard rock]] of Bowie's previous album ''The Man Who Sold the World'', ''Hunky Dory'' saw the partial return of the fey pop singer of ''Space Oddity'', with light fare such as \"[[Kooks (song)|Kooks]]\" and the cover \"Fill Your Heart\" sitting alongside heavier material like the [[occult]]-tinged \"[[Quicksand (David Bowie song)|Quicksand]]\" (whose lyric mentions the Golden Dawn (i.e. the [[Hermetic Order of the Golden Dawn]]) and [[Aleister Crowley]]) and the semi-autobiographical \"[[The Bewlay Brothers]]\". Between the two extremes was \"[[Oh! You Pretty Things]]\", whose pop tune hid lyrics, inspired by [[Friedrich Nietzsche|Nietzsche]], predicting the imminent replacement of modern man by \"the [[\u00dcbermensch|Homo Superior]]\", and which has been cited as a direct precursor to \"[[Starman (song)|Starman]]\" from Bowie's next album, ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]''.{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|p=44}}\n\n== Title and artwork ==\nAlthough Bowie generally left naming his albums until last minute, the title, 'Hunky Dory', was announced at the John Peel session.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=606}} It was suggested by Bob Grace of Chrysalis, who got the idea from an [[Esher]] pub landlord and formerly of the [[Royal Air Force]]. He told Peter and Leni Gillman, the authors of ''Alias David Bowie'', that the landlord had an unusual vocabulary that was \"peppered with upper-crust jargon\", using words such as 'prang' and 'whizzo', and phrases such as 'everything's hunky-dory'. Grace told Bowie and he loved it.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|pp=606\u2013607}} Pegg notes that there was a song from 1957 by the American doo-wop band the Guytones also titled \"Hunky Dory\" that may have played a part as well.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=607}} Spitz notes that 'hunky-dory' is an English slang term that means everything is right in the world.{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=156}} The album's sleeve would bear the credit \"Produced by Ken Scott (assisted by the actor)\". The \"actor\" was Bowie himself, whose \"pet conceit\", in the words of ''[[NME]]'' critics [[Roy Carr]] and [[Charles Shaar Murray]], was \"to think of himself as an actor\".{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|pp=7\u201311}}\n\nThe cover artwork was taken by photographer Brian Ward at his [[Heddon Street]] studio,{{sfn|Pegg|2016|pp=610\u2013611}} who was introduced to Bowie by Grace. One idea was for Bowie to dress as an Egyptian Pharoah, partly inspired by the British media's infatuation with the [[British Museum]]'s new [[Tutankhamun]] exhibit.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=610}} Photos of Bowie posing as a sphinx and in a lotus position were taken \u2013 one of them was released as part of the 1990 ''Space Oddity'' reissue \u2013 but the idea was ultimately not chosen. Bowie later recalled: \"We didn't run with it, as they say. Probably a good idea.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=610}} Rather than something extravagant, Bowie opted for a more minimalist image reflecting the album's \"preoccupation with the silver screen.\" Bowie later said: \"I was into Oxford bags, and there are a pair, indeed, on the back of the album. [I was attempting] what I presumed was kind of an [[Evelyn Waugh]] Oxbridge look.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=611}} The final image is a close-up of Bowie looking up into space as he pushes his hair back from his forehead. Originally shot in monochrome, the image was re-coloured by illustrator Terry Pastor, who recently set up the Main Artery design studio in [[Covent Garden]] with George Underwood; Pastor would later design the cover and sleeve for ''Ziggy Stardust''.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=611}} Pegg writes: \"Bowie's decision to use a re-coloured photo suggests a hand-tinted lobby-card from the days of the silent cinema and, simultaneously, Warhol's famous ''[[Marilyn Diptych]]'' screen-prints.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=611}} Robert Dimery, in his book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]'', also notes the influenced of Warhol's ''Dietrich'' prints and writes that Bowie took a photo book that contained multiple ''Dietrich'' prints with him to the photoshoot.<ref>{{cite book |title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die |last=Dimery |first=Robert |year=2005 |publisher=Quintet Publishing |location=London |isbn=978-1-84403-392-8 |page=[https://archive.org/details/1001albumsyoumus0000unse_l0q0/page/254 254] |url=https://archive.org/details/1001albumsyoumus0000unse_l0q0/page/254 }}</ref>\n\n== Release and aftermath ==\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Erlewine AllMusic\">{{cite web|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|title=''Hunky Dory'' \u2013 David Bowie|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/hunky-dory-mw0000189509|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=13 March 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615072909/http://www.allmusic.com/album/hunky-dory-mw0000189509|archive-date=15 June 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n|rev2score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=David Bowie: Hunky Dory|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?ID=3887|work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|issue=47|date=May 2006|accessdate=14 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070823012137/http://www.blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?ID=3887|archivedate=23 August 2007}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n|rev3score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Kot|first=Greg|authorlink=Greg Kot|title=Bowie's Many Faces Are Profiled on Compact Disc|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-06-10/entertainment/9002170173_1_space-oddity-scary-monsters-ziggy-stardust|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=10 June 1990|accessdate=14 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416150839/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-06-10/entertainment/9002170173_1_space-oddity-scary-monsters-ziggy-stardust|archive-date=16 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n|rev4Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|edition=5th concise|year=2011|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin (writer)|isbn=0-85712-595-8|chapter=David Bowie}}</ref>\n|rev5 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n|rev5score = 10/10<ref name=\"Wolk Pitchfork\">{{cite web|last=Wolk|first=Douglas|authorlink=Douglas Wolk|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/21066-five-years-1969-1973/|title=David Bowie: ''Five Years 1969\u20131973''|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=1 October 2015|accessdate=21 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160206231305/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/21066-five-years-1969-1973/|archive-date=6 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev6 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|rev6score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sheffield|first=Rob|authorlink=Rob Sheffield|title=David Bowie: ''Hunky Dory'' (reissue)|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/cd/review.asp?aid=50071&cf=331|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=18 March 1999|accessdate=14 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031003202846/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/cd/review.asp?aid=50071&cf=331|archivedate=3 October 2003}}</ref>\n|rev7 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n|rev7Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Sheffield|first=Rob|authorlink=Rob Sheffield|chapter=David Bowie|title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]|editor1-last=Brackett|editor1-first=Nathan|editor2-last=Hoard|editor2-first=Christian|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|edition=4th|year=2004|pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/97 97\u201399]|isbn=0-7432-0169-8}}</ref>\n|rev8 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n|rev8score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dolan|first=Jon|title=How to Buy: David Bowie|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s5jfV6kXmTEC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA84|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|volume=22|issue=7|date=July 2006|accessdate=14 July 2016|page=84|journal=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002175230/https://books.google.com/books?id=s5jfV6kXmTEC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA84|archive-date=2 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev9 = ''[[Spin Alternative Record Guide]]''\n|rev9score = 9/10{{sfn|Weisbard|Marks|1995|page=55}}\n|rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n|rev10Score = A\u2212<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cg22.php|title=Consumer Guide (22)|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York|date=30 December 1971|accessdate=28 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815194640/http://robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cg22.php|archive-date=15 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\nFollowing the success of Peter Noone's version of \"Oh! You Pretty Things\", Defries sought to extricate Bowie from his contract with [[Mercury Records]], the label that distributed Bowie's previous two albums.{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=195\u2013196}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=603}} Although his contract was to expire in June 1971, Mercury had intended to renew it with improved terms. However, Defries succeeded in forcing Mercury to terminate his contract in May after threatening to deliver a low-quality album.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|pp=605\u2013606}} Defries was then able to pay off Bowie's debts to Mercury through Gem Productions; Mercury then surrendered their copyright on ''[[David Bowie (1969 album)|David Bowie]]'' (1969) and ''The Man Who Sold the World'' (1970).{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=606}} After ending the contract with Mercury, Defries presented the album to multiple labels in the US. [[RCA Records]], stationed in New York City, liked the album and signed Bowie to a three-album deal on 9 September 1971; RCA would be Bowie's label for the rest of the 1970s.{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=195, 227}} \n\n''Hunky Dory'' was released by RCA on 17 December 1971.<ref name=buckstrange1 />{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|p=40}} Supported by the single \"Changes\", the album scored generally favourable reviews and sold reasonably well on its initial release, without being a major success.{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|pp=7\u201311}} ''[[Melody Maker]]'' called it \"the most inventive piece of song-writing to have appeared on record in a considerable time\", while ''[[NME]]'' described it as Bowie \"at his brilliant best\".<ref name=pegg>{{cite book |title=The Complete David Bowie |last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |authorlink=Nicholas Pegg |year=2004 |origyear=2000 |edition= |publisher=Reynolds & Hearn Ltd |location=London |isbn=1-903111-73-0 |pages=265\u201372}}</ref> In the United States, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' opined that \"''Hunky Dory'' not only represents Bowie's most engaging album musically, but also finds him once more writing literally enough to let the listener examine his ideas comfortably, without having to withstand a barrage of seemingly impregnable verbiage before getting at an idea\".<ref name=rs>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/hunky-dory-19720106 |title=Hunky Dory |author=Mendelsohn, John |accessdate=27 October 2014 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110180003/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/hunky-dory-19720106 |archive-date=10 November 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, it was only after the commercial breakthrough of ''Ziggy Stardust'' in mid-1972 that ''Hunky Dory'' became a hit, climbing to number 3 in the UK<ref name=mojo0702>{{cite journal |last=Sheppard |first=David |date=February 2007 |title=60 Years of Bowie |journal=[[Mojo (magazine)|MOJO Classic]] |page=24}}</ref> and remaining on the [[UK Albums Chart|chart]] for 69 weeks.<ref name=\"auto\">*Roberts, David (editor). ''[[British Hit Singles & Albums|The Guinness Book of British Hit Albums]]'', p71. Guinness Publishing Ltd. 7th edition (1996). {{ISBN|0-85112-619-7}}</ref> In 1973, RCA released \"[[Life on Mars?]]\" as a single, which also made number 3 in the UK.<ref name=buckstrange2>{{cite book |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |last=Buckley |first=David |year=2000 |origyear=1999 |publisher=Virgin Books |location=London |isbn=0-7535-0457-X |page=624}}</ref> A reissue returned the album, in January 1981, to the British chart, where it remained for 51 weeks.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] praised the album writing, \"On the surface, [having] such a wide range of styles and sounds would make an album incoherent, but Bowie's improved songwriting and determined sense of style instead made ''Hunky Dory'' a touchstone for reinterpreting pop's traditions into fresh, postmodern pop music.\"<ref name=\"Erlewine AllMusic\" /> In 1998, ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' magazine readers voted ''Hunky Dory'' the 43rd greatest album of all time, while in 2000 the same magazine placed it at number 16 in its list of the 100 Greatest British Albums Ever. It was also voted number 23 in [[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]'s ''[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]'' 3rd Edition (2000)''.'' In 2003, the album was ranked 107th on ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s list of [[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]], and 108 in a 2012 revised list.<ref name=\"RS 500\">{{cite web| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/david-bowie-hunky-dory-172127/| year=2012| title=500 Greatest Albums: ''Hunky Dory'' \u2013 David Bowie| website=[[Rolling Stone]]| accessdate=19 September 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023215941/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/david-bowie-hunky-dory-172127/| archive-date=23 October 2019| url-status=live}}</ref> In the same year, [[VH1]] placed it 47th and the Virgin [[All Time Top 1000 Albums]] chart placed it at number 16. In 2004, it was ranked 80th on ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''<nowiki/>'s Top 100 Albums of the 1970s. In 2006, ''[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]'' magazine chose it as one of the 100 best albums of all time.<ref name=time>{{cite magazine|author=[[Josh Tyrangiel]]|author2=[[Alan Light]]|title=The All-TIME 100 Albums|accessdate=7 July 2014|date=26 January 2010|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]|url=http://www.time.com/time/2006/100albums/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109195005/http://www.time.com/time/2006/100albums/index.html|archive-date=9 November 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> According to [[Acclaimed Music]], it is the 70th most celebrated album in popular music history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/album/A214.htm|title=Hunky Dory ranked 70th most celebrated album|work=Acclaimed Music|access-date=15 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811085236/http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/album/A214.htm|archive-date=11 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBowie himself considered the album to be one of the most important in his career. Speaking in 1999, he said: \"''Hunky Dory'' gave me a fabulous groundswell. I guess it provided me, for the first time in my life, with an actual audience \u2013 I mean, people actually coming up to me and saying, 'Good album, good songs.' That hadn't happened to me before. It was like, 'Ah, I'm getting it, I'm finding my feet. I'm starting to communicate what I want to do. Now: what is it I want to do?' There was always a double whammy there.\"<ref>Chris Roberts interview with David Bowie in ''Uncut'', October 1999, Issue 29.</ref> Spitz writes that many artists have their \"it all came together on this one\" record, naming the likes of ''[[Beggars Banquet]]'' by [[the Rolling Stones]], ''[[Damn the Torpedoes (album)|Damn the Torpedoes]]'' by [[Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers]], ''[[War (U2 album)|War]]'' by [[U2]] and ''[[The Bends (album)|The Bends]]'' by [[Radiohead]]. \"For David Bowie, it's ''Hunky Dory''.\"{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=158}}\n\n== Track listing ==\nAll tracks written by [[David Bowie]], except where noted.<ref name=\"liner notes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=Hunky Dory|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1971|publisher=[[RCA Records]]|location=UK|type=liner notes|id=SF 8244}}</ref>\n\n;Side one\n# \"[[Changes (David Bowie song)|Changes]]\" \u2013 3:37\n# \"[[Oh! You Pretty Things]]\" \u2013 3:12\n# \"Eight Line Poem\" \u2013 2:55\n# \"[[Life on Mars (song)|Life on Mars?]]\" \u2013 3:43\n# \"[[Kooks (song)|Kooks]]\" \u2013 2:53\n# \"[[Quicksand (David Bowie song)|Quicksand]]\" \u2013 5:08\n\n;Side two\n# \"Fill Your Heart\" ([[Biff Rose]], [[Paul Williams (songwriter)|Paul Williams]]) \u2013 3:07\n# \"[[Andy Warhol (song)|Andy Warhol]]\" \u2013 3:56\n# \"[[Song for Bob Dylan]]\" \u2013 4:12\n# \"[[Queen Bitch]]\" \u2013 3:18\n# \"[[The Bewlay Brothers]]\" \u2013 5:22\n\n* Sides one and two were combined as tracks 1\u201311 on CD reissues.\n\n== CD releases ==\n\n=== 1980s and 1990s ===\n\nFollowing its initial release on compact disc in the mid-1980s, ''Hunky Dory'' was re-released in CD format in 1990, by [[Rykodisc]]/[[EMI]], with bonus tracks.<ref>{{Cite AV media notes|title=Hunky Dory|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1990|publisher=[[EMI]]/Rykodisc|location=UK|type=liner notes|id=EMC 3572}}</ref>\n\n;Bonus tracks (1990 Rykodisc)\n# \"[[Bombers (David Bowie song)|Bombers]]\" (Previously unreleased track, recorded in 1971, mixed 1990; there is a very rare LP sampler issued by RCA prior to the release of the album with the GEM logo on the cover and \"Bombers\" appears followed by the linking cross talk that leads into \"Andy Warhol,\" clearly indicating that Bowie had originally intended it to be the opening track on the second side [instead of \"Fill Your Heart\"]) \u2013 2:38\n# \"[[The Supermen]]\" (Alternate version recorded on 12 November 1971 during sessions for ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]'', originally released on ''[[Glastonbury Fayre (album)|Revelations \u2013 A Musical Anthology for Glastonbury Fayre]]'' in July 1972, compiled by the organisers of the [[Glastonbury Festival]] at which Bowie had played in 1971<ref name=ZSCChanges2>{{cite web |url=http://www.5years.com/ziggy30th2cd.htm |title=EMI 30th Anniversary 2CD Limited Edition (2002) |work=The Ziggy Stardust Companion |accessdate=22 June 2008 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/66YQHIclR?url=http://www.5years.com/ziggy30th2cd.htm |archive-date=30 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>) \u2013 2:41\n# \"Quicksand\" (Demo version, recorded in 1971, mixed 1990) \u2013 4:43\n# \"The Bewlay Brothers\" (Alternate mix) \u2013 5:19\n\nIn 1999, the album was reissued by Virgin/EMI (7243 521899 0 8), without bonus tracks, but with 24-bit digitally remastered sound. This edition was re-pressed in 2014 by Parlophone/Warner Music Group, having acquired the Virgin-owned Bowie catalogue.\n\n=== 2015 remaster ===\n\nIn 2015, the album was remastered for the ''[[Five Years (1969\u20131973)]]'' [[box set]].<ref>[http://www.davidbowie.com/news/five-years-1969-1973-box-set-due-september-54571 FIVE YEARS 1969 \u2013 1973 box set due September] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160218235114/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/five-years-1969-1973-box-set-due-september-54571 |date=18 February 2016 }} at davidbowie.com</ref> It was released in CD, vinyl, and digital formats, both as part of this compilation and separately.<ref>[http://www.superdeluxeedition.com/news/david-bowie-five-years-vinyl-available-separately-next-month David Bowie / 'Five Years' vinyl available separately next month] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216222656/http://www.superdeluxeedition.com/news/david-bowie-five-years-vinyl-available-separately-next-month |date=16 February 2016 }} at superdeluxeedition.com</ref>\n\n== Personnel ==\nAlbum credits per [[Nicholas Pegg]].{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=603}}\n*[[David Bowie]] \u2013 vocals, guitar, [[alto saxophone|alto]] and [[tenor saxophone]], piano (in \"Oh! You Pretty Things\" (together with Rick Wakeman<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uncut.co.uk/news/rick-wakeman-reveals-played-piano-david-bowies-oh-pretty-things-98931|title=Rick Wakeman reveals he played piano on David Bowie's \"Oh! You Pretty Things\" - Uncut|author=|date=17 January 2017|website=uncut.co.uk|access-date=17 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118144242/http://www.uncut.co.uk/news/rick-wakeman-reveals-played-piano-david-bowies-oh-pretty-things-98931|archive-date=18 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/entertainment-arts-38627868/david-bowie-song-question-answered-by-rick-wakeman|title=Bowie or Wakeman piano mystery|author=|date=17 May 2018|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com|access-date=21 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721193608/https://www.bbc.com/news/av/entertainment-arts-38627868/david-bowie-song-question-answered-by-rick-wakeman|archive-date=21 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>), \"Eight Line Poem\" and \"The Bewlay Brothers\")\n*[[Mick Ronson]] \u2013 guitar, vocals, [[Mellotron]], arrangements\n*[[Trevor Bolder]] \u2013 bass guitar, trumpet\n*[[Mick Woodmansey]] \u2013 drums\n*[[Rick Wakeman]] \u2013 piano\n\n'''Production'''\n*[[Ken Scott]] \u2013 producer, [[recording engineer]], [[audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing engineer]]\n*David Bowie \u2013 producer\n*Dr. Toby Mountain \u2013 [[audio mastering|remastering engineer]] (for Rykodisc release)\n*Jonathan Wyner \u2013 assistant remastering engineer, mixing engineer (for Rykodisc release)\n*[[Peter Mew]] \u2013 remastering engineer (for EMI release)\n*Nigel Reeve \u2013 assistant remastering engineer (for EMI release)\n*[[George Underwood (artist)|George Underwood]] \u2013 cover art\n\n== Charts ==\n'''Album'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Chart\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|1972\n|[[UK Albums Chart]]<ref name=ukt40>{{cite web|url=http://www.everyhit.com |title=UK Top 40 Hit Database |accessdate=23 June 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080319091720/http://everyhit.com/ |archivedate=19 March 2008 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|1972\n|Norwegian Albums Chart\n|align=\"center\"|33\n|-\n|1972\n|Australian Albums Chart\n|align=\"center\"|39\n|-\n|2016\n|New Zealand Albums Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/albums?chart=4190|title=The Official New Zealand Music Chart|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122121614/http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/albums?chart=4190|archive-date=22 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|30\n|-\n|2016\n|US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=allmusicalbumcharts>{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r2480|pure_url=yes}} |title=(((Hunky Dory > Charts & Awards > Billboard Albums))) |accessdate=23 June 2008 |work=AllMusic}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|57\n|-\n|2016\n{{albumchart|BillboardCatalog|4|artist=David Bowie|accessdate=30 January 2016}}\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Single'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Single\n!Chart\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|1972\n|\"Changes\"\n|[[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=allmusicsinglescharts>{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r2480|pure_url=yes}} |title=(((Hunky Dory > Charts & Awards > Billboard Singles))) |accessdate=23 June 2008 |work=Allmusic}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|66\n|-\n|1973\n|\"Life on Mars?\"\n|[[UK Singles Chart]]<ref name=ukt40 />\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|1975\n|\"Changes\"\n|''Billboard'' Pop Singles<ref name=allmusicsinglescharts />\n|align=\"center\"|41\n|}\n\n== Certifications ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n!Organization\n!Level\n!Date\n|-\n|[[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]] \u2013 UK\n|Gold\n|{{start date|df=yes|1982|1|25}}<ref name=bpi>{{cite web |url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/ |title=BPI Certified Awards |accessdate=23 June 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318142521/https://www.bpi.co.uk/ |archive-date=18 March 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n|BPI \u2013 UK\n|Platinum\n|{{start date|df=yes|1982|1|25}}<ref name=bpi />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n;Sources\n*{{cite book |last=Buckley |first=David |year=2005 |origyear=1999 |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |location=London |publisher=Virgin |isbn=978-0-75351-002-5 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Cann |first=Kevin |year=2010 |title=Any Day Now \u2013 David Bowie: The London Years: 1947\u20131974 |publisher=Adelita |isbn=978-0-95520-177-6 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Carr |first1=Roy|authorlink1=Roy Carr |last2=Murray |first2=Charles Shaar| authorlink2=Charles Shaar Murray |year=1981 |title=Bowie: An Illustrated Record |publisher=Eel Pie Pub |isbn=978-0-38077-966-6|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Doggett |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Doggett |year=2012 |title=The Man Who Sold the World: David Bowie and the 1970s |publisher=[[HarperCollins|HarperCollins Publishers]] |isbn=978-0-06-202466-4 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |title=The Complete David Bowie |publisher=[[Titan Books]] |edition=7th |location=London |year=2016 |isbn=978-1-78565-365-0 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Spitz |first=Marc |author-link1=Marc Spitz |title=Bowie: A Biography |publisher=[[Crown Publishing Group]] |year=2009  |isbn=978-0-307-71699-6|title-link=Bowie: A Biography |location=New York |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Weisbard |editor1-first=Eric |editor2-last=Marks |editor2-first=Craig |title=[[Spin Alternative Record Guide]] |publisher=[[Vintage Books]] |year=1995 |isbn=0-679-75574-8 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{David Bowie}}\n\n[[Category:David Bowie albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Ken Scott]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Trident Studios]]\n[[Category:EMI Records albums]]\n[[Category:RCA Records albums]]\n[[Category:1971 albums]]\n[[Category:Rykodisc albums]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records albums]]\n[[Category:Parlophone albums]]\n", "name_user": "Zmbro", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground:wrong word", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hunky_Dory"}
{"title_page": "Harold Ambler", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Harold Ambler|timestamp=20200420160454|year=2020|month=April|day=20|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Harold Ambler|date=20 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Puffery|date=April 2020}}\n{{Notability|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{short description|American author, musician, teacher and surfer}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Harold Ambler\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Harold Ambler.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = Harold Ambler, Yosemite, California, 2009\n| caption          = Harold Ambler, Yosemite, California, 2009\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth year and age|1965}}\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MMpuff|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = Author, Teacher, Musician\n| language         = \n| residence        = Rhode Island\n| nationality      = United States\n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = Dartmouth College, Columbia University\n| home_town        = [[La Jolla, California]]\n| period           = \n| genre            = <!-- or: | genres = -->\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notable_works    = \n| spouse           = Kim Edge-Ambler <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = 2\n| relatives        = \n| awards           = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = \n| module           = \n| website          = {{URL|https://talkingabouttheweather.wordpress.com/}} \n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc.; or omit -->\n}}\n'''Harold Ambler''' (born 1965) is an American author, musician, and teacher. Ambler was noted for his 2009 article on [[HuffPost|Huffington Post]], entitled \"[[Al Gore|Mr. Gore]]: Apology Accepted\" in which he said, \"Mr. Gore has stated, regarding climate change, that 'the science is in.' Well, he is absolutely right about that, except for one tiny thing. It is the biggest whopper ever sold to the public in the history of humankind.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/harold-ambler/mr-gore-apology-accepted_b_154982.html|title=Harold Ambler: Mr. Gore: Apology Accepted|date=2009-01-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121190820/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/harold-ambler/mr-gore-apology-accepted_b_154982.html|access-date=2020-04-07|archive-date=2009-01-21}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAfter the article was published on Huffington Post, it was widely criticized, and Huffington Post published an \"update\" by [[Arianna Huffington|Ariana Huffington]] stating \"we have an editorial process in place. The associate blog editor published the post. It was an error in judgment. I would not have posted it. Although HuffPost welcomes a vigorous debate on many subjects, I am a firm believer that there are not two sides to every issue, and that on some issues the jury is no longer out. The climate crisis is one of these issues.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/huffington-post-blows-it_b_155696|title=Huffington Post Blows It With Recycled Climate Skeptic Nonsense|last=Roberts|first=David|last2=Writer|first2=ContributorStaff|date=2009-02-06|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07|last3=Grist.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://huffingtonpost.com/kevin-grandia/on-global-warming-is-it-h_b_155379.html|title=Kevin Grandia: On Global Warming is it Harold Ambler or the Royal Society?|date=2009-02-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207223039/http://huffingtonpost.com/kevin-grandia/on-global-warming-is-it-h_b_155379.html|access-date=2020-04-07|archive-date=2009-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123112048552052989|title=Notable & Quotable|date=2009-01-05|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 Ambler was interviewed about the Huffington Post controversy and other topics including his book on [[Brown University men's rowing|Brown Crew]], and his upcoming book on Climate in an appearance on [[Fox News]] Red Eye with [[Greg Gutfeld]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talkingabouttheweather.wordpress.com/2009/07/09/how-is-the-weather-where-you-are/|title=How Is the Weather Where You Are?|last=Ambler|first=Harold|date=2009-07-09|website=Talking About the Weather|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite document|title=Harold Ambler on Global Warming, FOX News Red Eye|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live}}</ref>  In 2011 Ambler's book, ''Don't Sell Your Coat, Surprising Truths About Climate Change'' was published.<ref name=\":0\" /> In March 2012 Ambler was interviewed by Ann Marie Spatharakis on [[WBLQ (AM)|WBLQ]] of Westerly, Rhode Island,<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|title=Harold Ambler on WBLQ|via=SoundCloud}}</ref> and was later interviewed about music and more on Spatharakis' WBLQ show \"Inside the Studio.\" and also appeared for interviews on Spatharakis' WBLQ show \"Inside the Studio.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/ann-marie-spatharakis/sets/author-and-musiciam-harold|title=Author and Musician Harold Ambler In the Studio with Ann Marie Spatharakis|website=SoundCloud|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Education and work background==\nAmbler was educated at [[Dartmouth College|Dartmouth]] and [[Columbia University|Columbia]] and started his journalism career at [[The New Yorker]]. His writing has appeared in The [[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]], The Huffington Post, The [[The Atlantic|AtlanticWire]], [[New York Daily News]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103235936/https://www.nydailynews.com/opinion/cool-climate-change-article-1.1195746|title=Let's all cool it on climate change: Horrific hurricanes aren't anything new - NY Daily News|last=Ambler|first=Harold|date=2012-11-03|website=web.archive.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103235936/https://www.nydailynews.com/opinion/cool-climate-change-article-1.1195746|archive-date=2012-11-03|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and [[Watts Up With That?|wattsupwiththat]].com.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wattsupwiththat.com/2014/06/29/antarctica-sets-new-record-for-sea-ice-area/|title=Antarctica sets new record for sea ice area|last=Ambler|first=Harold|date=June 29, 2014|website=WattsUpWithThat.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> In 2008 while living in Austin, Texas, his album \"Carousel\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCuoqTq2PUKEZw37mpZqNVDQ|title=Harold Ambler - Topic|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> was released by Big Day Records, after recording sessions in 2003 and 2005 in Massachusetts,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.cdbaby.com/|title=CD Baby Music Store|website=store.cdbaby.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and was reviewed favorably by the Austin Chronicle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2008-08-08/658188/|title=Harold Ambler: Carousel Album Review|last=Freeman|first=Doug|last2=Fri.|website=www.austinchronicle.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07|last3=Aug. 8|last4=2008}}</ref> Ambler performed music in Austin regularly from 2007 to 2009.<ref>{{Cite book|last=The Austin Chronicle|url=http://archive.org/details/The_Austin_Chronicle-2007-03-16|title=The Austin Chronicle 2007-03-16|date=2007-03-16|language=english}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=The Austin Chronicle|url=http://archive.org/details/The_Austin_Chronicle-2008-05-30|title=The Austin Chronicle 2008-05-30|date=2008-05-30|language=english}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=The Austin Chronicle|url=http://archive.org/details/The_Austin_Chronicle-2009-03-27|title=The Austin Chronicle 2009-03-27|date=2009-03-27|language=english}}</ref> He performed at the Wakefield, RI inaugural River Fest, Oktoberfest in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independentri.com/independentri_com/article_01d40e09-1b40-513c-95e8-f165e33e5182.html|title=Wakefield to host inaugural River Fest, Oktoberfest|last=Editor|first=Helena Touhey/ Features|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> As of August 2019, Ambler performs music at local venues in Rhode Island.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linesiderbrewing.com/other-events/2019/4/11/pints-amp-poses|title=HAROLD AMBLER \u2014 LineSider Brewing Co.|date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406092254/https://www.linesiderbrewing.com/other-events/2019/4/11/pints-amp-poses|access-date=2020-04-07|archive-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nAmbler co-wrote and edited a 600-page history of [[Brown_University_men's_rowing#cite_note-autogenerated1-3 | rowing for Brown University]], ''Ever True: The History of Brown Crew'', published in March 2009.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Joukowsky|first=Artemis|url=https://books.google.com/?id=j1UhmwEACAAJ|title=Ever True: The History of Brown Crew|last2=Ambler|first2=Harold|last3=Philips|first3=David M.|last4=Albert|first4=Christian, H. M.|last5=Hooper|first5=Marcia|date=2010|isbn=978-0-9845146-0-1|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Geake|first=Robert A.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iHt_CQAAQBAJ&pg=PT111&dq=ever+true+brown+rowing#v=onepage|title=A History of the Providence River: With the Moshassuck, Woonasquatucket & Seekonk Tributaries|date=2013-02-19|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=978-1-61423-881-2|language=en}}</ref> In 2011 Ambler's book, ''Don't Sell Your Coat, Surprising Truths About Climate Change'' was published by Lansing International Books.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Ambler|first=Harold|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NN2bpwAACAAJ|title=Don't Sell Your Coat: Surprising Truths about Climate Change|date=2011-12-15|publisher=Lansing International Books|isbn=978-0-615-56904-8|location=|pages=5, 10\u201313|language=en}}</ref> In May 2012, Ambler co-wrote an article, \"Climategate Continues\" in [[National Review]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2012/05/climategate-continues-andrew-montford-harold-ambler/|title=Climategate Continues|date=2012-05-24|website=National Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> In June 2012, Ambler was a guest on [[Media_Research_Center#MRCTV |MRC TV]], where he explained his views on Hillary Clinton's visit to the Arctic Ice Shelf, and manipulation of politicians' views on climate change.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mrctv.org/embed/113600|title=Weather Wise-Guys Discuss Hillary Clinton's Recent Tour of the Arctic Ice Shelf {{!}} MRCTV|website=MRCTV|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>(2:20-5:15) In March 2012, in a letter published in the Wall Street Journal, Ambler stated he received no money from \"Big Oil,\" but mainstream climate scientists had received more than $1 billion from energy companies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304692804577283493572669670|title=My Oily Millions|date=2012-03-20|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\n==Personal background==\nAmbler was born in 1965 in La Jolla, California. He grew up near San Francisco, and graduated from Henry M. Gunn High School in Palo Alto in 1983. In 1987, he graduated from Dartmouth College with a bachelor\u2019s degree in English. In 1989, he received a master\u2019s in English from Columbia University. For three more years he did work toward a Ph.D., studying the work of [[Samuel Beckett]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talkingabouttheweather.wordpress.com/2012/02/11/harold-ambler-wikipedia/|title=Harold Ambler Wikipedia|last=Ambler|first=Harold|date=2012-02-11|website=Talking About the Weather|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Ambler lives in Rhode Island and  teaches at Rocky Hill School, a private school in East Greenwich.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180904/heat-related-early-dismissals-tough-call-for-ri-schools|title=Heat-related early dismissals a tough call for R.I. schools|last=Borg|first=Linda|website=providencejournal.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nAmbler says he has been \"obsessed\" with weather and climate from a young age, and has studied both ever since. With English degrees from Dartmouth and Columbia, his  career started in journalism at The New Yorker magazine, from 1993 to 1999. His work has appeared in The Wall Street Journal, The Huffington Post, The AtlanticWire (the Atlantic Monthly\u2019s online presence), Watts Up With That?, The Providence Journal,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.providencejournal.com/article/20130921/Opinion/309219936|title=Harold Ambler: Here comes fall, so clear the decks for clarity of mind|last=Ambler|first=Harold|website=providencejournal.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Rhode Island Monthly, and Brown Alumni Monthly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.golocalprov.com/business/brown-grads-dominating-business-in-the-united-states|title=Brown Grads Dominating Business in the United States|last=Fenton|first=Josh|website=GoLocalProv|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> On his blog, Ambler describes himself as a nature-loving person, and a [[Surfing|surfer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talkingabouttheweather.wordpress.com/2014/05/28/i-am-a-nature-loving-person/|title=I am a nature-loving person|last=Ambler|first=Harold|date=2014-05-28|website=Talking About the Weather|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nAmbler says he was \"once an adherent of the view that human activity was dangerously raising Earth's temperature and changing its climate in destructive ways,\" but in 2008 an article by [[Khabibullo Abdussamatov]] prompted him to study \"the evidence presented by global warming skeptics.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Ambler is married to painter and illustrator Kim Edge-Ambler, and has two daughters,<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wattsupwiththat.com/2011/12/16/dont-sell-your-coat/|title=Don't sell your coat!|date=2011-12-16|website=Watts Up With That?|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> one of whom was \"traumatized\" by an evacuation drill in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independentri.com/independents/north_east/east_greenwich/article_a5e252e9-24ac-5d8f-873e-97f746652e49.html|title=Second-grader 'traumatized' by evacuation drill, parent says|last=Writer|first=Joseph R. LaPlante Staff|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> \n\n==Reception==\nIn a March 2009 interview on Fox News Red Eye,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0qsQoSqG-6s|title=Harold Ambler on Global Warming, FOX News Red Eye|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Ambler was asked his opinion of an upcoming jet trip and speech by Prince Charles to say the world has less than 100 months to act to avoid irreversible climate changes. He also was asked to discuss the background and aftermath of his Huffington Post piece published the previous January, and to respond to challenges to his background and qualifications to question climate \"theology\" as a musician and sports enthusiast, without formal science background. Ambler also explained the connection between his book, Ever True, about rowing, and his interest in climate, saying as an outdoors person with background in water polo, surfing and rowing, he had a long-term, deep interest in both weather and climate, and \"as a concerned citizen, he has the right to study and comment\" as much or more than most celebrities. \n\nIn his book, ''The Joy of Hate: How to Triumph Over Whiners in the Age of Phony Outrage'', [[Greg Gutfeld|Greg Gutfield]] described Ambler as a \"delightful gentleman\" you should know, someone who worked \"in all the right places\" including The New Yorker, a singer in a band, a rower, a blogger, and a liberal. He also described the personal backlash toward Ambler as being treated as a heretic or a leper, discussed a \"hate speech\" threat against Ambler, which he declined to prosecute, and quoted Ambler saying, \"It's witch-burning all over again,\" in response to the hatred directed at him.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gutfeld|first=Greg|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_liPDQAAQBAJ&dq=%22harold+ambler%22&q=%22harold+ambler%22#v=snippet&q=%22harold%20ambler%22&f=false|title=The Joy of Hate: How to Triumph Over Whiners in the Age of Phony Outrage|date=2014-01-07|publisher=Crown Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-98698-6|location=|pages=209\u2013211|language=en}}</ref> \n\n[[DeSmogBlog|DeSmog blog]] was critical of Ambler's writing on Huffington Post.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.desmogblog.com/directory/vocabulary/3878|title=harold ambler|website=DeSmog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> On January 8 and 9, 2009, Senator [[Jim Inhofe|James Inhofe]] discussed Ambler's Huffington Post article in Senate speeches.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?283206-102/senate-session|title=Senate Session {{!}} C-SPAN.org|website=www.c-span.org|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?283244-1/senate-session|title=Senate Session {{!}} C-SPAN.org|website=www.c-span.org|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> In his 2010 book, ''Straight Up'', [[Joe Romm|Joseph Romm]] criticized Ambler and his Huntington Post article, but referred to blog posts for \"detailed debunking.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Romm|first=Joseph J.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4TP4ff08mbQC&pg=PA165&dq=harold+ambler#v=onepage|title=Straight Up: America's Fiercest Climate Blogger Takes on the Status Quo Media, Politicians, and Clean Energy Solutions|date=2010-04-08|publisher=Island Press|isbn=978-1-59726-795-3|location=|pages=165\u2013166|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012 Bj\u00f8rn Strong of Oslo Afternoon Post was critical of Ambler's arguments in ''Don't Sell Your Coat.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aftenposten.no/article/ap-xPQdX.html|title=Intet nytt fra klimaskeptikerne|last=Spaltist|first=Bj\u00f8rn St\u00e6rk|website=Aftenposten|language=nb-NO|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In a \"snapshot analysis report,\" the [[Union of Concerned Scientists]] (UCS) used Ambler's April 2012 appearance on Fox News as one of four \"illustrative examples\" of \"denigrating climate science.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/resrep00040?Search=yes&resultItemClick=true&searchText=%22Harold+Ambler%22&searchUri=/action/doBasicSearch?Query=%2522Harold+Ambler%2522&amp;acc=on&amp;wc=on&ab_segments=0/basic_SYC-5152/test|title=Is News Corp. Failing Science?: Representations of Climate Science on Fox News Channel and in the Wall Street Journal Opinion Pages on JSTOR|last=|first=|date=September 1, 2012|website=www.jstor.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* {{IMDb name|nm5001734|Harold Ambler}}\n* [https://www.broadjam.com/haroldambler Harold Ambler at Broadjam]\n* [https://www.huffpost.com/author/harold-ambler Harold Ambler at Huffington Post]\n* [https://talkingabouttheweather.wordpress.com/ Harold Ambler Blog]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140517120024/http://haroldambler.com/ Harold Ambler (archived) website]\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American writers]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:American musicians]]\n[[Category:American surfers]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n[[Category:American rowers]]\n[[Category:American journalists]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Harold Ambler|timestamp=20200420160454|year=2020|month=April|day=20|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Harold Ambler|date=20 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Puffery|date=April 2020}}\n{{Notability|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{short description|American author, musician, teacher and surfer}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Harold Ambler\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Harold Ambler.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = Harold Ambler, Yosemite, California, 2009\n| caption          = Harold Ambler, Yosemite, California, 2009\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth year and age|1965}}\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MMpuff|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = Author, Teacher, Musician\n| language         = \n| residence        = Rhode Island\n| nationality      = United States\n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = Dartmouth College, Columbia University\n| home_town        = [[La Jolla, California]]\n| period           = \n| genre            = <!-- or: | genres = -->\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notable_works    = \n| spouse           = Kim Edge-Ambler <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = 2\n| relatives        = \n| awards           = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = \n| module           = \n| website          = {{URL|https://talkingabouttheweather.wordpress.com/}} \n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc.; or omit -->\n}}\n'''Harold Ambler''' (born 1965) is an American author, musician, and teacher. Ambler was noted for his 2009 article on [[HuffPost|Huffington Post]], entitled \"[[Al Gore|Mr. Gore]]: Apology Accepted\" in which he said, \"Mr. Gore has stated, regarding climate change, that 'the science is in.' Well, he is absolutely right about that, except for one tiny thing. It is the biggest whopper ever sold to the public in the history of humankind.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/harold-ambler/mr-gore-apology-accepted_b_154982.html|title=Harold Ambler: Mr. Gore: Apology Accepted|date=2009-01-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121190820/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/harold-ambler/mr-gore-apology-accepted_b_154982.html|access-date=2020-04-07|archive-date=2009-01-21}}</ref>\n\nAfter the article was published on Huffington Post, it was widely criticized, and Huffington Post published an \"update\" by [[Arianna Huffington|Ariana Huffington]] stating \"we have an editorial process in place. The associate blog editor published the post. It was an error in judgment. I would not have posted it. Although HuffPost welcomes a vigorous debate on many subjects, I am a firm believer that there are not two sides to every issue, and that on some issues the jury is no longer out. The climate crisis is one of these issues.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/huffington-post-blows-it_b_155696|title=Huffington Post Blows It With Recycled Climate Skeptic Nonsense|last=Roberts|first=David|last2=Writer|first2=ContributorStaff|date=2009-02-06|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07|last3=Grist.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://huffingtonpost.com/kevin-grandia/on-global-warming-is-it-h_b_155379.html|title=Kevin Grandia: On Global Warming is it Harold Ambler or the Royal Society?|date=2009-02-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207223039/http://huffingtonpost.com/kevin-grandia/on-global-warming-is-it-h_b_155379.html|access-date=2020-04-07|archive-date=2009-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123112048552052989|title=Notable & Quotable|date=2009-01-05|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 Ambler was interviewed about the Huffington Post controversy and other topics including his book on [[Brown University men's rowing|Brown Crew]], and his upcoming book on Climate in an appearance on [[Fox News]] Red Eye with [[Greg Gutfeld]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talkingabouttheweather.wordpress.com/2009/07/09/how-is-the-weather-where-you-are/|title=How Is the Weather Where You Are?|last=Ambler|first=Harold|date=2009-07-09|website=Talking About the Weather|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite document|title=Harold Ambler on Global Warming, FOX News Red Eye|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live}}</ref>  In 2011 Ambler's book, ''Don't Sell Your Coat, Surprising Truths About Climate Change'' was published.<ref name=\":0\" /> In March 2012 Ambler was interviewed by Ann Marie Spatharakis on [[WBLQ (AM)|WBLQ]] of Westerly, Rhode Island,<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|title=Harold Ambler on WBLQ|via=SoundCloud}}</ref> and was later interviewed about music and more on Spatharakis' WBLQ show \"Inside the Studio.\" and also appeared for interviews on Spatharakis' WBLQ show \"Inside the Studio.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/ann-marie-spatharakis/sets/author-and-musiciam-harold|title=Author and Musician Harold Ambler In the Studio with Ann Marie Spatharakis|website=SoundCloud|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Education and work background==\nAmbler was educated at [[Dartmouth College|Dartmouth]] and [[Columbia University|Columbia]] and started his journalism career at [[The New Yorker]]. His writing has appeared in The [[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]], The Huffington Post, The [[The Atlantic|AtlanticWire]], [[New York Daily News]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103235936/https://www.nydailynews.com/opinion/cool-climate-change-article-1.1195746|title=Let's all cool it on climate change: Horrific hurricanes aren't anything new - NY Daily News|last=Ambler|first=Harold|date=2012-11-03|website=web.archive.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103235936/https://www.nydailynews.com/opinion/cool-climate-change-article-1.1195746|archive-date=2012-11-03|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and [[Watts Up With That?|wattsupwiththat]].com.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wattsupwiththat.com/2014/06/29/antarctica-sets-new-record-for-sea-ice-area/|title=Antarctica sets new record for sea ice area|last=Ambler|first=Harold|date=June 29, 2014|website=WattsUpWithThat.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> In 2008 while living in Austin, Texas, his album \"Carousel\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCuoqTq2PUKEZw37mpZqNVDQ|title=Harold Ambler - Topic|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> was released by Big Day Records, after recording sessions in 2003 and 2005 in Massachusetts,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.cdbaby.com/|title=CD Baby Music Store|website=store.cdbaby.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and was reviewed favorably by the Austin Chronicle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2008-08-08/658188/|title=Harold Ambler: Carousel Album Review|last=Freeman|first=Doug|last2=Fri.|website=www.austinchronicle.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07|last3=Aug. 8|last4=2008}}</ref> Ambler performed music in Austin regularly from 2007 to 2009.<ref>{{Cite book|last=The Austin Chronicle|url=http://archive.org/details/The_Austin_Chronicle-2007-03-16|title=The Austin Chronicle 2007-03-16|date=2007-03-16|language=english}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=The Austin Chronicle|url=http://archive.org/details/The_Austin_Chronicle-2008-05-30|title=The Austin Chronicle 2008-05-30|date=2008-05-30|language=english}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=The Austin Chronicle|url=http://archive.org/details/The_Austin_Chronicle-2009-03-27|title=The Austin Chronicle 2009-03-27|date=2009-03-27|language=english}}</ref> He performed at the Wakefield, RI inaugural River Fest, Oktoberfest in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independentri.com/independentri_com/article_01d40e09-1b40-513c-95e8-f165e33e5182.html|title=Wakefield to host inaugural River Fest, Oktoberfest|last=Editor|first=Helena Touhey/ Features|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> As of August 2019, Ambler performs music at local venues in Rhode Island.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linesiderbrewing.com/other-events/2019/4/11/pints-amp-poses|title=HAROLD AMBLER \u2014 LineSider Brewing Co.|date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406092254/https://www.linesiderbrewing.com/other-events/2019/4/11/pints-amp-poses|access-date=2020-04-07|archive-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nAmbler co-wrote and edited a 600-page history of [[Brown_University_men's_rowing#cite_note-autogenerated1-3 | rowing for Brown University]], ''Ever True: The History of Brown Crew'', published in March 2009.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Joukowsky|first=Artemis|url=https://books.google.com/?id=j1UhmwEACAAJ|title=Ever True: The History of Brown Crew|last2=Ambler|first2=Harold|last3=Philips|first3=David M.|last4=Albert|first4=Christian, H. M.|last5=Hooper|first5=Marcia|date=2010|isbn=978-0-9845146-0-1|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Geake|first=Robert A.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iHt_CQAAQBAJ&pg=PT111&dq=ever+true+brown+rowing#v=onepage|title=A History of the Providence River: With the Moshassuck, Woonasquatucket & Seekonk Tributaries|date=2013-02-19|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=978-1-61423-881-2|language=en}}</ref> In 2011 Ambler's book, ''Don't Sell Your Coat, Surprising Truths About Climate Change'' was published by Lansing International Books.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Ambler|first=Harold|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NN2bpwAACAAJ|title=Don't Sell Your Coat: Surprising Truths about Climate Change|date=2011-12-15|publisher=Lansing International Books|isbn=978-0-615-56904-8|location=|pages=5, 10\u201313|language=en}}</ref> In May 2012, Ambler co-wrote an article, \"Climategate Continues\" in [[National Review]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2012/05/climategate-continues-andrew-montford-harold-ambler/|title=Climategate Continues|date=2012-05-24|website=National Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> In June 2012, Ambler was a guest on [[Media_Research_Center#MRCTV |MRC TV]], where he explained his views on Hillary Clinton's visit to the Arctic Ice Shelf, and manipulation of politicians' views on climate change.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mrctv.org/embed/113600|title=Weather Wise-Guys Discuss Hillary Clinton's Recent Tour of the Arctic Ice Shelf {{!}} MRCTV|website=MRCTV|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>(2:20-5:15) In March 2012, in a letter published in the Wall Street Journal, Ambler stated he received no money from \"Big Oil,\" but mainstream climate scientists had received more than $1 billion from energy companies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304692804577283493572669670|title=My Oily Millions|date=2012-03-20|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\n==Personal background==\nAmbler was born in 1965 in La Jolla, California. He grew up near San Francisco, and graduated from Henry M. Gunn High School in Palo Alto in 1983. In 1987, he graduated from Dartmouth College with a bachelor\u2019s degree in English. In 1989, he received a master\u2019s in English from Columbia University. For three more years he did work toward a Ph.D., studying the work of [[Samuel Beckett]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talkingabouttheweather.wordpress.com/2012/02/11/harold-ambler-wikipedia/|title=Harold Ambler Wikipedia|last=Ambler|first=Harold|date=2012-02-11|website=Talking About the Weather|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Ambler lives in Rhode Island and  teaches at Rocky Hill School, a private school in East Greenwich.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180904/heat-related-early-dismissals-tough-call-for-ri-schools|title=Heat-related early dismissals a tough call for R.I. schools|last=Borg|first=Linda|website=providencejournal.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nAmbler says he has been \"obsessed\" with weather and climate from a young age, and has studied both ever since. With English degrees from Dartmouth and Columbia, his  career started in journalism at The New Yorker magazine, from 1993 to 1999. His work has appeared in The Wall Street Journal, The Huffington Post, The AtlanticWire (the Atlantic Monthly\u2019s online presence), Watts Up With That?, The Providence Journal,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.providencejournal.com/article/20130921/Opinion/309219936|title=Harold Ambler: Here comes fall, so clear the decks for clarity of mind|last=Ambler|first=Harold|website=providencejournal.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Rhode Island Monthly, and Brown Alumni Monthly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.golocalprov.com/business/brown-grads-dominating-business-in-the-united-states|title=Brown Grads Dominating Business in the United States|last=Fenton|first=Josh|website=GoLocalProv|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> On his blog, Ambler describes himself as a nature-loving person, and a [[Surfing|surfer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talkingabouttheweather.wordpress.com/2014/05/28/i-am-a-nature-loving-person/|title=I am a nature-loving person|last=Ambler|first=Harold|date=2014-05-28|website=Talking About the Weather|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nAmbler says he was \"once an adherent of the view that human activity was dangerously raising Earth's temperature and changing its climate in destructive ways,\" but in 2008 an article by [[Khabibullo Abdussamatov]] prompted him to study \"the evidence presented by global warming skeptics.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Ambler is married to painter and illustrator Kim Edge-Ambler, and has two daughters,<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wattsupwiththat.com/2011/12/16/dont-sell-your-coat/|title=Don't sell your coat!|date=2011-12-16|website=Watts Up With That?|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> one of whom was \"traumatized\" by an evacuation drill in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independentri.com/independents/north_east/east_greenwich/article_a5e252e9-24ac-5d8f-873e-97f746652e49.html|title=Second-grader 'traumatized' by evacuation drill, parent says|last=Writer|first=Joseph R. LaPlante Staff|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> \n\n==Reception==\nIn a March 2009 interview on Fox News Red Eye,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0qsQoSqG-6s|title=Harold Ambler on Global Warming, FOX News Red Eye|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Ambler was asked his opinion of an upcoming jet trip and speech by Prince Charles to say the world has less than 100 months to act to avoid irreversible climate changes. He also was asked to discuss the background and aftermath of his Huffington Post piece published the previous January, and to respond to challenges to his background and qualifications to question climate \"theology\" as a musician and sports enthusiast, without formal science background. Ambler also explained the connection between his book, Ever True, about rowing, and his interest in climate, saying as an outdoors person with background in water polo, surfing and rowing, he had a long-term, deep interest in both weather and climate, and \"as a concerned citizen, he has the right to study and comment\" as much or more than most celebrities. \n\nIn his book, ''The Joy of Hate: How to Triumph Over Whiners in the Age of Phony Outrage'', [[Greg Gutfeld|Greg Gutfield]] described Ambler as a \"delightful gentleman\" you should know, someone who worked \"in all the right places\" including The New Yorker, a singer in a band, a rower, a blogger, and a liberal. He also described the personal backlash toward Ambler as being treated as a heretic or a leper, discussed a \"hate speech\" threat against Ambler, which he declined to prosecute, and quoted Ambler saying, \"It's witch-burning all over again,\" in response to the hatred directed at him.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gutfeld|first=Greg|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_liPDQAAQBAJ&dq=%22harold+ambler%22&q=%22harold+ambler%22#v=snippet&q=%22harold%20ambler%22&f=false|title=The Joy of Hate: How to Triumph Over Whiners in the Age of Phony Outrage|date=2014-01-07|publisher=Crown Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-98698-6|location=|pages=209\u2013211|language=en}}</ref> \n\n[[DeSmogBlog|DeSmog blog]] was critical of Ambler's writing on Huffington Post.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.desmogblog.com/directory/vocabulary/3878|title=harold ambler|website=DeSmog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> On January 8 and 9, 2009, Senator [[Jim Inhofe|James Inhofe]] discussed Ambler's Huffington Post article in Senate speeches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?283206-102/senate-session|title=Senate Session {{!}} C-SPAN.org|website=www.c-span.org|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?283244-1/senate-session|title=Senate Session {{!}} C-SPAN.org|website=www.c-span.org|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> In his 2010 book, ''Straight Up'', [[Joe Romm|Joseph Romm]] criticized Ambler and his Huntington Post article, but referred to blog posts for \"detailed debunking.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Romm|first=Joseph J.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4TP4ff08mbQC&pg=PA165&dq=harold+ambler#v=onepage|title=Straight Up: America's Fiercest Climate Blogger Takes on the Status Quo Media, Politicians, and Clean Energy Solutions|date=2010-04-08|publisher=Island Press|isbn=978-1-59726-795-3|location=|pages=165\u2013166|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012 Bj\u00f8rn Strong of Oslo Afternoon Post was critical of Ambler's arguments in ''Don't Sell Your Coat.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aftenposten.no/article/ap-xPQdX.html|title=Intet nytt fra klimaskeptikerne|last=Spaltist|first=Bj\u00f8rn St\u00e6rk|website=Aftenposten|language=nb-NO|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In a \"snapshot analysis report,\" the [[Union of Concerned Scientists]] (UCS) used Ambler's April 2012 appearance on Fox News as one of four \"illustrative examples\" of \"denigrating climate science.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/resrep00040?Search=yes&resultItemClick=true&searchText=%22Harold+Ambler%22&searchUri=/action/doBasicSearch?Query=%2522Harold+Ambler%2522&amp;acc=on&amp;wc=on&ab_segments=0/basic_SYC-5152/test|title=Is News Corp. Failing Science?: Representations of Climate Science on Fox News Channel and in the Wall Street Journal Opinion Pages on JSTOR|last=|first=|date=September 1, 2012|website=www.jstor.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* {{IMDb name|nm5001734|Harold Ambler}}\n* [https://www.broadjam.com/haroldambler Harold Ambler at Broadjam]\n* [https://www.huffpost.com/author/harold-ambler Harold Ambler at Huffington Post]\n* [https://talkingabouttheweather.wordpress.com/ Harold Ambler Blog]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140517120024/http://haroldambler.com/ Harold Ambler (archived) website]\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American writers]]\n[[